{"title_page": "Victor Marijnen", "text_new": "{{short description|39th Prime Minister of the Netherlands}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix   = \n|name               = Victor Marijnen\n|image              = Victor Marijnen 1963 (1).jpg\n|imagesize          = 250px\n|caption            = Victor Marijnen in 1963\n|office             = [[Prime Minister of the Netherlands]]\n|term_start         = 24 July 1963\n|term_end           = 14 April 1965\n|monarch            = [[Juliana of the Netherlands|Juliana]]\n|deputy             = [[Barend Biesheuvel]]\n|predecessor        = [[Jan de Quay]]\n|successor          = [[Jo Cals]]\n|office1            = [[List of mayors of The Hague|Mayor of The Hague]]\n|term_start1        = 16 October 1968\n|term_end1          = 5 April 1975\n|predecessor1       = [[Hans Kolfschoten]]\n|successor1         = Lien Vos-van Gortel <br/> <small>(''Ad interim'')</small>\n|office2            = [[Rijnmond|Chairman of the <br/> Rijnmond Council]]\n|term_start2        = 20 May 1965\n|term_end2          = 16 October 1968\n|predecessor2       = ''Office established''\n|successor2         = Willem Fibbe\n|office3            = [[House of Representatives (Netherlands)|Member of the House of Representatives]]\n|term_start3        = 27 April 1965 \n|term_end3          = 14 January 1966\n|term_start4        = 2 July 1963\n|term_end4          = 24 July 1963\n|parliamentarygroup4= [[Catholic People's Party]]\n|office5            = [[List of Ministers of Social Affairs of the Netherlands|Minister of Social Affairs]] [[List of Ministers of Health of the Netherlands|and Health]]\n|term_start5        = 3 July 1961 \n|term_end5          = 17 July 1961 <br/> <small>''Ad interim''</small>\n|primeminister5     = [[Jan de Quay]]\n|predecessor5       = [[Charles van Rooy]]\n|successor5         = [[Gerard Veldkamp]]\n|office6            = [[List of Ministers of Agriculture of the Netherlands|Minister of Agriculture and Fisheries]]\n|term_start6        = 19 May 1959\n|term_end6          = 24 July 1963\n|primeminister6     = [[Jan de Quay]]\n|predecessor6       = [[Kees Staf]] <br/> <small>as Minister of Agriculture, <br/> Fisheries and Food Supplies</small>\n|successor6         = [[Barend Biesheuvel]]\n|office7            = [[Social and Economic Council|Member of the Social <br/> and Economic Council]]\n|term_start7        = 1 November 1957\n|term_end7          = 19 May 1959\n|1blankname7        = {{nowrap|Chairman}}\n|1namedata7         = [[Frans de Vries]] <br/> <small>(1957\u20131958)</small> <br/> [[Gerard Verrijn Stuart]] <br/> <small>(1958\u20131959)</small>\n|birthname          = Victor Gerard Marie Marijnen \n|birth_date         = {{Birth date|df=y|1917|02|21}}\n|birth_place        = [[Arnhem]], [[Netherlands]]\n|death_date         = {{Death date and age|df=y|1975|04|05|1917|02|21}}\n|death_place        = [[The Hague]], [[Netherlands]]\n|nationality        = [[Netherlands|Dutch]]\n|death_cause        = [[Myocardial infarction|Heart attack]]\n|party              = [[Catholic People's Party]] <br/> <small>(from 1945)</small>\n|otherparty         = [[Roman Catholic State Party|Roman Catholic <br/> State Party]] <small>(until 1945)</small>\n|spouse             = {{marriage|Mini Schreurs|22 May 1944|5 April 1975|reason=his death}}\n|children           = 4 sons and 2 daughters\n|residence          = \n|alma_mater         = [[Radboud University Nijmegen]] <br/> <small>([[Bachelor of Laws]], [[Master of Laws]])</small> <br/> [[Erasmus University Rotterdam|Rotterdam School of Economics]] <br/> <small>([[Bachelor of Economics]])</small>\n|occupation         = [[Politician]] \u00b7 [[Civil service|Civil servant]] \u00b7 [[Jurist]] \u00b7 [[Economist]] \u00b7 [[Nonprofit organization|Nonprofit director]] \u00b7 [[Trade association|Trade association executive]] \u00b7 [[Academic administration|Academic administrator]] \u00b7 [[Lobbying|Lobbyist]]\n|signature          = \n}}\n\n'''Victor Gerard Marie \"Vic\" Marijnen''' (21 February 1917 \u2013 5 April 1975) was a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] politician of the defunct [[Catholic People's Party]] (KVP) now merged into the [[Christian Democratic Appeal]] (CDA) party. He was a jurist who served as [[Prime Minister of the Netherlands]] from 24 July 1963 until 14 April 1965.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://resources.huygens.knaw.nl/bwn1880-2000/lemmata/bwn2/marijnen|title=Marijnen, Victor Gerard Marie (1917-1975)|publisher=Huygens ING|date=12 November 2013|accessdate=20 May 2019|language=nl}}</ref>\n\nMarijnen applied at the [[Radboud University Nijmegen]] in June 1936 [[Major (academic)|majoring]] in [[Law]] and obtaining an [[Bachelor of Laws]] degree in July 1938 before graduating with an [[Master of Laws]] degree in July 1941. Marijnen worked as a civil servant for the [[Ministry of Economic Affairs and Climate Policy (Netherlands)|Ministry of Commerce, Industry and Shipping]] and the [[Ministry of Agriculture, Nature and Food Quality|Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries]] from August 1941 until May 1944, and for the [[Ministry of Economic Affairs and Climate Policy (Netherlands)|Ministry of Commerce, Industry]] [[Ministry of Agriculture, Nature and Food Quality|and Agriculture]] from May 1944 until October 1945, and for the Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food Supplies from October 1945 until February 1949. Marijnen applied at the [[Erasmus University Rotterdam|Rotterdam School of Economics]] in December 1945 for a [[postgraduate education]] and obtained an [[Bachelor of Economics]] degree in December 1946. Marijnen worked as a trade association executive for the [[:nl:LTO Nederland|Christian Farmers and Gardeners Association]] (CBTB) and served as General-Secretary from February 1949 until April 1951. Marijnen worked again for the Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food Supplies from April 1951 until November 1957 as Deputy Director-General of the department for Agricultural Trade from April 1951 until January 1953. He served as Director-General of the department for Agricultural Trade from January 1953 until November 1957. Marijnen worked as a trade association executive for the [[VNO-NCW|Catholic Employers association]] (AKWV) and served as General-Secretary from November 1957 until May 1959. After the [[1959 Dutch general election|election of 1959]] Marijnen was appointed as [[List of Ministers of Agriculture of the Netherlands|Minister of Agriculture and Fisheries]] in the [[De Quay cabinet|Cabinet De Quay]], taking office on 19 May 1959. Marijnen served as acting [[List of Ministers of Social Affairs of the Netherlands|Minister of Social Affairs]] [[List of Ministers of Health of the Netherlands|and Health]] from 3 July 1961 until 17 July 1961 following the resignation of [[Charles van Rooy]]. Marijnen was elected as a [[House of Representatives (Netherlands)|Member of the House of Representatives]] after the [[1963 Dutch general election|election of 1963]], taking office on 2 July 1963.\n\nFollowing several failed cabinet formation attempts, Marijnen was approached by the [[Catholic People's Party#Organisation|Leader of the Catholic People's Party]] [[Wim de Kort]] as a candidate for Prime Minister, Marijnen accepted and was appointed as [[Formateur]] to form a new cabinet. The following [[Dutch cabinet formation|cabinet formation of 1963]] resulted in a coalition agreement between the Catholic People's Party, the [[People's Party for Freedom and Democracy]] (VVD), the [[Anti-Revolutionary Party]] (ARP) and the [[Christian Historical Union]] (CHU) which formed the [[Marijnen cabinet|Cabinet Marijnen]] with Marijnen becoming [[Prime Minister of the Netherlands]] and [[Ministry of General Affairs|Minister of General Affairs]], taking office on 24 July 1963. The Cabinet Marijnen fell on 27 February 1965 following a disagreement in the coalition about proposed reforms to the [[Dutch public broadcasting system|public broadcasting system]] and continued to serve in a [[Demissionary cabinet|demissionary]] capacity until the [[Dutch cabinet formation|cabinet formation of 1965]] with Marijnen not giving a cabinet post in the new [[Cals cabinet|cabinet]], the Cabinet Marijnen was replaced by the [[Cals cabinet|Cabinet Cals]] on 14 April 1965. \n\nMarijnen returned as Member of the House of Representatives taking the place of his successor as Prime Minister [[Jo Cals]], taking office on 27 April 1965 and continued to serve in the House of Representatives as a [[backbencher]] until his resignation on 14 January 1966. Marijnen also became active in the [[public sector]] and occupied numerous seats as a nonprofit director on several boards of directors and supervisory boards ([[Radboud University Nijmegen]], [[International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement|International Red Cross Netherlands]]) and served on several [[:nl:Staatscommissie|state commissions]] and councils on behalf of the government ([[Ministry of Housing, Spatial Planning and the Environment (Netherlands)|Advisory Council for Spatial Planning]], [[:nl:Raad voor Cultuur|Council for Culture]] and [[KPN]]). On 12 May 1965, Marijnen was nominated as the first [[Rijnmond|Chairman of the Rijnmond Council]], a [[direct election|direct electable]] sub national administrative layer between the [[List of municipalities of the Netherlands|municipalities]] and the [[Provinces of the Netherlands|provinces]] in the [[Rijnmond|Rijnmond Area]], taking office on 20 May 1965. In September 1968, Marijnen was nominated as [[List of mayors of The Hague|Mayor of The Hague]], he resigned as Chairman of the Rijnmond Council the day he was installed as Mayor, taking office on 16 October 1968. On 5 April 1975 Marijnen died after suffering a fatal [[Myocardial infarction|heart Attack]] at his home in The Hague.\n\nMarijnen was known for his abilities as a [[Management|manager]] and [[Consensus decision-making|consensus builder]]. During his premiership, his cabinet was responsible for reforms to [[health insurance]], the handling of the marriage between [[Princess Irene of the Netherlands|Princess Irene]] and [[Carlos Hugo, Duke of Parma|Carlos Hugo of Bourbon-Parma]] and the proposed reforms to the [[Dutch public broadcasting system|public broadcasting system]].\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life===\nVictor Gerard Marie Marijnen was born in [[Arnhem]] on 21 February 1917. In 1941 he graduated in law from the [[Radboud University Nijmegen]] and went on to work in the accountancy divisions of the [[Ministry of Agriculture, Nature and Food Quality]]. In 1945 he was seconded to the Council for the Restitution of Legal Rights.\n\nIn 1949 Marijnen became secretary of the Agricultural Society and in 1951 Secretary-General of the Foreign Agricultural Trade Department of the [[Ministry of Agriculture, Nature and Food Quality]]. From 1957 he was secretary of the General Catholic Employers Association and the Catholic Federation of Employers Associations.\n\n[[File:Lyndon B Johnson in Holland De vice-president en premier Marijnen op Ypenburg, Bestanddeelnr 915-7144.jpg|thumb|left|220px|Prime Minister Victor Marijnen and [[Vice President of the United States]] [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] at [[Ypenburg Airport]] on 5 november 1963.]]\n\n====Accusations regarding paedophile priests====\nIn 1956 Marijnen was chairman of a children's home in [[Gelderland]] where children, including [[Henk Heithuis]], were [[sexual abuse|sexually abused]] by priests. According to the ''Telegraph'' newspaper, reporting in March 2012, he \"intervened to have prison sentences dropped against several priests convicted of abusing children.\"<ref name=\"Protecting paedophile priests\">{{cite web | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/netherlands/9153676/Dutch-Roman-Catholic-Church-castrated-at-least-10-boys.html | title=Dutch Roman Catholic Church 'castrated at least 10 boys' | publisher=Telegraph | accessdate=March 19, 2012}}</ref> The Dutch Catholic Church organised the [[castration]] of Heithuis while he lived at the Gelderland children's home in 1956 after he reported being sexually abused to the police.<ref name=\"Protecting paedophile priests\"/>\n\n===Politics===\nIn the [[De Quay cabinet]], Marijnen was [[Ministry of Agriculture, Nature and Food Quality|Minister of Agriculture and Fisheries]]. He served as [[Prime Minister of the Netherlands]] from 24 July 1963 until 14 April 1965. \n\nThe [[natural gas]] reserves, recently found in [[Slochteren]] were a considerable boost for the economy. This, combined with [[labour shortage]] led to a rise in wages and the attraction of foreign workers. Despite this being the second cabinet without socialist [[Labour Party (Netherlands)|Labour Party]], the building up of a [[welfare state]], that was started after [[World War II]], continued with the introduction of [[minimum wages]] in 1964 and the [[Universal health care|national health service]]. In 1965, measures were taken against [[commercial television]] stations transmitting from the [[North Sea]]. The cabinet finally fell over the issue if commercial TV should be allowed in the Netherlands.\n\nFrom 1965 to 1966 Marijnen was a member of the [[House of Representatives (Netherlands)|House of Representatives]] and concurrently chairman of the Board of the Rijnmond Authority. In 1967 he was also appointed chairman of the Post and Telecommunications Council. On 16 October 1968 he was selected [[List of mayors of The Hague|Mayor of The Hague]].\n\nMarijnen died on 5 April 1975 in [[The Hague]], while serving as Mayor from a [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]] at the age of 58.\n\n==Decorations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:60%;\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccf; text-align:center;\"\n| colspan=5 |'''Honours'''\n|-\n! style=\"width:80px;\"| Ribbon bar !! Honour !! Country !! Date !! Comment\n|-\n| [[File:NLD Order of Orange-Nassau - Grand Officer BAR.png|80px]]\n| [[Order (distinction)|Grand Officer]] of the [[Order of Orange-Nassau]]\n| Netherlands\n| 20 April 1965\n| \n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n\n* {{in lang|nl}} [https://www.parlement.com/id/vg09ll36p2yd/v_g_m_victor_marijnen Mr. V.G.M. (Victor) Marijnen] Parlement & Politiek\n* {{in lang|nl}} [https://www.rijksoverheid.nl/regering/over-de-regering/kabinetten-sinds-1945/kabinet-marijnen Kabinet-Marijnen] Rijksoverheid\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Kees Staf]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Ministers of Agriculture of the Netherlands|Minister of Agriculture and Fisheries]]|years=1959\u20131963}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Barend Biesheuvel]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Charles van Rooy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Ministers of Social Affairs of the Netherlands|Minister of Social Affairs]] [[List of Ministers of Health of the Netherlands|and Health]] <br/> <small>''Ad interim''</small>|years=1961}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Gerard Veldkamp]]}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Jan de Quay]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of the Netherlands]]|years=1963\u20131965}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after=[[Jo Cals]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of General Affairs|Minister of General Affairs]]|years=1963\u20131965}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Hans Kolfschoten]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of mayors of The Hague|Mayor of The Hague]]|years=1968\u20131975}}\n{{s-aft|after=Lien Vos-van Gortel <br/> <small>''Ad interim''</small>}}\n{{s-civ}}\n{{s-bef|before=''Unknown''}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Deputy Director-General of the <br/> Department for Agricultural Trade <br/> of the [[Ministry of Agriculture, Nature and Food Quality|Ministry of Agriculture, <br/> Fisheries and Food Supplies]]|years=1951\u20131953}}\n{{s-aft|after=''Unknown''}}\n{{s-bef|before=''Unknown''}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Director-General of the <br/> Department for Agricultural Trade <br/> of the [[Ministry of Agriculture, Nature and Food Quality|Ministry of Agriculture, <br/> Fisheries and Food Supplies]]|years=1953\u20131957}}\n{{s-aft|after=''Unknown''}}\n{{s-bef|before=''Unknown''}} \n{{s-ttl|title=Chairman of the <br/> [[Ministry of 