{"title_page": "Kingbeare", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|static_image=  \n|static_image_caption= \n|country= England\n|map_type=Cornwall\n|region= South West England\n|official_name= Kingbeare\n|cornish_name=  \n|civil_parish= [[Linkinhorne]]\n|unitary_england=     [[Cornwall Council|Cornwall]]\n|lieutenancy_england =[[Cornwall]]\n|os_grid_reference= SX271748\n|coordinates = {{coord|50.547|-4.442|display=inline,title}}\n|population =\n|population_ref = \n|post_town= [[Launceston, Cornwall|Launceston]]\n|postcode_area=   PL\n|postcode_district= PL15 7\n|dial_code=\n\n|hide_services=yes\n}}\n'''Kingbeare''' is a [[Hamlet (place)|hamlet]] in the parish of [[Linkinhorne]], [[Cornwall]], England.<ref name=OS201>{{cite map|title=Ordnance Survey: Landranger map sheet 201 ''Plymouth & Launceston''|ISBN=978-0-319-23287-3|publisher=Ordnance Survey}}</ref><ref>[http://www.explorebritain.info/locality-cornwall-kingbeare-sx2774 Kingbeare]; Explore Britain</ref> It is in the [[civil parish]] of [[North Hill, Cornwall]]\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Cornwall|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Hamlets in Cornwall]]\n\n\n{{Cornwall-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|static_image=  \n|static_image_caption= \n|country= England\n|map_type=Cornwall\n|region= South West England\n|official_name= Kingbeare\n|cornish_name=  \n|civil_parish= [[Linkinhorne]]\n|unitary_england=     [[Cornwall Council|Cornwall]]\n|lieutenancy_england =[[Cornwall]]\n|os_grid_reference= SX271748\n|coordinates = {{coord|50.547|-4.442|display=inline,title}}\n|population =\n|population_ref = \n|post_town= [[Launceston, Cornwall|Launceston]]\n|postcode_area=   PL\n|postcode_district= PL15 7\n|dial_code=\n\n|hide_services=yes\n}}\n'''Kingbeare''' is a [[Hamlet (place)|hamlet]] in the parish of [[Linkinhorne]], [[Cornwall]], England.<ref name=OS201>{{cite map|title=Ordnance Survey: Landranger map sheet 201 ''Plymouth & Launceston''|ISBN=978-0-319-23287-3|publisher=Ordnance Survey}}</ref><ref>[http://www.explorebritain.info/locality-cornwall-kingbeare-sx2774 Kingbeare]; Explore Britain</ref> It is in the [[civil parish]] of [[North Hill, Cornwall]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Cornwall|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Hamlets in Cornwall]]\n\n\n{{Cornwall-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Gazamp", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:AddedPortal:Cornwall", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kingbeare"}
{"title_page": "Data erasure", "text_new": "'''Data erasure''' (sometimes referred to as '''data clearing''', '''data wiping''', or '''data destruction''') is a software-based method of [[overwriting]] the data that aims to completely destroy all [[Data remanence|electronic data residing]] on a [[hard disk drive]] or other [[digital media]] by using zeros and ones to overwrite data onto all sectors of the device. By overwriting the data on the storage device, the data is rendered unrecoverable and achieves data sanitization.\n\nIdeally, software designed for data erasure should:\n \n#Allow for selection of a specific standard, based on unique needs, and \n#Verify the overwriting method has been successful and removed data across the entire device.\n\nPermanent data erasure goes beyond basic [[file deletion]] commands, which only remove direct pointers to the data [[disk sector]]s and make the [[data recovery]] possible with common software tools. Unlike [[degaussing]] and physical destruction, which render the storage media unusable, data erasure removes all information while leaving the disk operable. New [[flash memory]]-based media implementations, such as [[solid-state drive]]s or [[USB flash drive]]s, can cause data erasure techniques to fail allowing [[remnant data]] to be recoverable.<ref name=\"m.wei\">{{cite web |title=Reliably Erasing Data From Flash-Based Solid State Drives |url=https://www.usenix.org/legacy/events/fast11/tech/full_papers/Wei.pdf |work=FAST '11: 9th USENIX Conference on File and Storage Technologies |accessdate=31 October 2013 |author1=Michael Wei |author2=Laura M. Grupp |author3=Frederick E. Spada |author4=Steven Swanson |format=PDF |quote=For sanitizing entire disks, built-in sanitize commands are effective when implemented correctly, and software techniques work most, but not all, of the time. We found that none of the available software techniques for sanitizing individual files were effective.}}</ref>\n\nSoftware-based overwriting uses a software application to write a stream of zeros, ones or meaningless pseudorandom data onto all sectors of a hard disk drive. There are key differentiators between data erasure and other overwriting methods, which can leave data intact and raise the risk of [[data breach]], [[identity theft]] or failure to achieve regulatory compliance. Many data eradication programs also provide [[#Number of overwrites needed|multiple overwrites]] so that they support recognized government and industry standards, though a single-pass overwrite is widely considered to be sufficient for modern hard disk drives. Good software should provide verification of data removal, which is necessary for meeting certain standards.\n\nTo protect the data on lost or stolen media, some data erasure applications remotely destroy the data if the password is incorrectly entered. Data erasure tools can also target specific data on a disk for routine erasure, providing a [[hacker (computer security)|hacking]] protection method that is less time-consuming than software encryption. [[Electronic hardware|Hardware]]/[[firmware]] encryption built into the drive itself or integrated controllers is a popular solution with no degradation in performance at all.\n\n==Encryption==\nWhen encryption is in place, data erasure acts as a complement to [[crypto-shredding]], or the practice of 'deleting' data by (only) deleting or overwriting the encryption keys. \nPresently, dedicated hardware/firmware encryption solutions can perform a 256-bit full [[Advanced Encryption Standard|AES encryption]] faster than the drive electronics can write the data. Drives with this capability are known as self-encrypting drives ([[Hardware-based full disk encryption|SEDs]]); they are present on most modern enterprise-level laptops and are increasingly used in the enterprise to protect the data. Changing the encryption key renders inaccessible all data stored on a SED, which is an easy and very fast method for achieving a 100% data erasure. Theft of an SED results in a physical asset loss, but the stored data is inaccessible without the decryption key that is not stored on a SED, assuming there are no effective attacks against AES or its implementation in the drive hardware.\n\n==Importance==\nInformation technology assets commonly hold large volumes of confidential data. [[Social security number]]s, credit card numbers, bank details, medical history and classified information are often stored on computer hard drives or [[Server (computing)|servers]]. These can inadvertently or intentionally make their way onto other media such as printers, [[Universal Serial Bus|USB]], [[Flash memory|flash]], [[Iomega Zip drive|Zip]], [[Iomega Jaz drive|Jaz]], and [[Iomega REV|REV]] drives.\n\n===Data breach===\nIncreased storage of sensitive data, combined with rapid technological change and the shorter lifespan of IT assets, has driven the need for permanent data erasure of electronic devices as they are retired or refurbished. Also, compromised networks and [[laptop theft]] and loss, as well as that of other portable media, are increasingly common sources of data breaches.\n\nIf data erasure does not occur when a disk is retired or lost, an organization or user faces a possibility that the data will be stolen and compromised, leading to identity theft, loss of corporate reputation, threats to regulatory compliance and financial impacts. Companies spend large amounts of money to make sure their data is erased when they discard disks.<ref name=breach>{{cite web|url=http://www.networkworld.com/news/2006/110206-data-breach-cost.html|title=Average data breach costs companies $5 million|author=Fontana, John|work=[[Network World]]|date=2006-11-02|accessdate=2010-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110808113930/http://www.networkworld.com/news/2006/110206-data-breach-cost.html|archive-date=8 August 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{dubious|The reference talks links to http://www.networkworld.com/news/2006/102506-data-breach-costs-rise-year.html as a source, but that doesn't support the claim at all|date=January 2012}} High-profile incidents of data theft include:<!-- date order -->\n* CardSystems Solutions (2005-06-19): Credit card breach exposes 40 million accounts.<ref>{{cite news|author=Evers, Joris |date=2005-06-19|url=http://www.zdnet.com.au/credit-card-breach-exposes-40-million-accounts-139197997.htm |title=Credit card breach exposes 40 million accounts |agency=[[CNET News]]|publisher=[[ZDNET]]|accessdate=2010-07-20}}</ref><!-- was dead link, correct title made recovery easy-->\n* Lifeblood (2008-02-13):  Missing laptops contain personal information including dates of birth and some Social Security numbers of 321,000.<ref>{{cite web| author=Powers, Mary |date=2008-02-13|url=http://www.commercialappeal.com/news/2008/feb/13/missing-lifeblood-laptops-personal-information-tho/ |title=Laptops missing with IDs of donors|work=[[Memphis Commercial Appeal]]|accessdate=2010-07-20}}</ref>\n* Hannaford (2008-03-17): Breach exposes 4.2 million credit, debit cards.<ref>{{cite news| author=Sharp, David |date=2008-03-17|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/23678909 |title=Breach exposes 4.2 million credit, debit cards.|agency= [[Associated Press]] |publisher=NBC News|accessdate=2010-07-20}}</ref>\n* Compass Bank (2008-03-21): Stolen hard drive contains 1,000,000 customer records.<ref>Vijayan, Jaikumar (2008-03-21). [http://www.computerworld.com/action/article.do?command=viewArticleBasic&articleId=9072198 \"Programmer who stole drive containing 1 million bank records gets 42 months\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070302144543/http://www.computerworld.com/action/article.do?command=viewArticleBasic |date=2 March 2007 }}. ''[[Computer World]].'' Retrieved 2010-07-20.</ref>\n* University of Florida College of Medicine, Jacksonville (2008-05-20): Photographs and identifying information of 1,900 on improperly disposed computer.<ref>[http://www.bizjournals.com/jacksonville/stories/2008/05/19/daily9.html \"UF warns patients of security breach\"]. ''[[Jacksonville Business Journal]].'' 2008-05-20. Retrieved 2010-07-20.</ref><!--was dead link,  title made retrieval tricky-->\n* Oklahoma Corporation Commission (2008-05-21): Server sold at auction compromises more than 5,000 Social Security numbers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/news/article.aspx?articleID=20080521_12_OKLAH32253  |title=OKC buyer finds sensitive information on server| agency=Associated Press|work=[[Tulsa World]] |date=2008-05-21 |accessdate=2010-07-20}}</ref>\n* Department of Finance, the Australian Electoral Commission and National Disability Insurance Agency (2017-11-02) - 50,000 Australians and 5000 Federal Public servant records.{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n===Regulatory compliance===\nStrict industry standards and government regulations are in place that force organizations to mitigate the risk of unauthorized exposure of confidential corporate and government data. Regulations in the [[United States]] include [[Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act|HIPAA]] (Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act); [[Fair and Accurate Credit Transactions Act|FACTA]] (The Fair and Accurate Credit Transactions Act of 2003); GLB ([[Gramm-Leach-Bliley Act|Gramm-Leach Bliley]]); [[Sarbanes-Oxley Act]] (SOx); and Payment Card Industry Data Security Standards ([[Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard|PCI DSS]]) and the [[Data Protection Act 1998|Data Protection Act]] in the [[United Kingdom]]. Failure to comply can result in fines and damage to company reputation, as well as civil and criminal liability.{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n===Preserving assets and the environment===\nData erasure offers an alternative to physical destruction and degaussing for secure removal of all the disk data. Physical destruction and degaussing destroy the digital media, requiring disposal and contributing to [[electronic waste]] while negatively impacting the [[carbon footprint]] of individuals and companies.<ref name=environment>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/2020/Technology/story?id=1479506 |title=Is America exporting a huge environmental problem?|publisher=[[ABC News]] |work=[[20/20 (US television series)|20/20]]| date=2006-01-06| accessdate=2010-07-20}}</ref> Hard drives are nearly 100% recyclable and can be collected at no charge from a variety of hard drive recyclers after they have been sanitized.{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n===Limitations===\nData erasure may not work completely on flash based media, such as [[Solid State Drive]]s and [[USB Flash Drive]]s, as these devices can store remnant data which is inaccessible to the erasure technique, and data can be retrieved from the individual flash memory chips inside the device.<ref name=\"m.wei\" />\nData erasure through overwriting only works on hard drives that are functioning and writing to all sectors. [[Bad sector]]s cannot usually be overwritten, but may contain recoverable information. Bad sectors, however, may be [[S.M.A.R.T.#Visibility to host systems|invisible]] to the host system and thus to the erasing software. [[Disk encryption software|Disk encryption]] before use prevents this problem. Software-driven data erasure could also be compromised by malicious code.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsa.gov/ia/_files/government/MDG/NSA_CSS_Storage_Device_Declassification_Manual.pdf|format=PDF|title=NSA/CSS Storage Device Declassification Manual|publisher=[[NSA]]|access-date=19 January 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160320074045/https://www.nsa.gov/ia/_files/government/MDG/NSA_CSS_Storage_Device_Declassification_Manual.pdf|archive-date=20 March 2016|url-status=dead}} This Manual 912 supersedes NSA/CSS Manual 1302, dated 10 November 2000.</ref>\n\n==Differentiators==\nSoftware-based data erasure uses a disk accessible application to write a combination of ones, zeroes and any other [[Alphanumeric character generator|alpha numeric character]] also known as the \"mask\" onto each hard disk drive sector. The level of [[security]] when using software data destruction tools are increased dramatically by pre-testing hard drives for sector abnormalities and ensuring that the drive is 100% in working order. The number of wipes has become obsolete with the more recent inclusion of a \"verify pass\" which scans all sectors of the disk and checks against what character should be there i.e.; 1 Pass of AA has to fill every writable sector of the hard disk. This makes any more than 1 Pass an unnecessary and certainly a more damaging act especially as drives have passed the 1TB mark.\n\n===Full disk overwriting===\nWhile there are many overwriting programs, only those capable of complete data erasure offer full security by destroying the data on all areas of a hard drive. Disk overwriting programs that cannot access the entire hard drive, including hidden/locked areas like the [[host protected area]] (HPA), [[device configuration overlay]] (DCO), and remapped sectors, perform an incomplete erasure, leaving some of the data intact. By accessing the entire hard drive, data erasure eliminates the risk of [[data remanence]].\n\nData erasure can also bypass the [[operating system|Operating System (OS)]]. Overwriting programs that operate through the OS will not always perform a complete erasure because they cannot modify the contents of the hard drive that are actively in use by that OS. Because of this, many data erasure programs like [[Darik's Boot and Nuke|DBAN]] are provided in a bootable format, where you run off of a [[live CD]] that has all of the necessary software to erase the disk.\n\n===Hardware support===\nData erasure can be deployed over a network to target multiple [[Personal computer|PCs]] rather than having to erase each one sequentially. In contrast with [[DOS]]-based overwriting programs that may not detect all network hardware, [[Linux]]-based data erasure software supports high-end server and [[storage area network]] (SAN) environments with hardware support for [[Serial ATA]], [[Serial Attached SCSI]] (SAS) and [[Fibre Channel]] disks and remapped sectors. It operates directly with sector sizes such as 520, 524, and 528, removing the need to first reformat back to 512 sector size. [[WinPE]] has now overtaken Linux as the environment of choice since drivers can be added with little effort. This also helps with data destruction of tablets and other handheld devices that require pure UEFI environments without hardware NIC's installed and/or are lacking UEFI network stack support.\n\n===Standards===\nMany government and industry standards exist for software-based overwriting that removes the data. A key factor in meeting these standards is the number of times the data is overwritten. Also, some standards require a method to verify that all the data have been removed from the entire hard drive and to view the overwrite pattern. Complete data erasure should account for hidden areas, typically DCO, HPA and remapped sectors.\n\nThe 1995 edition of the [[National Industrial Security Program]] Operating Manual (DoD 5220.22-M) permitted the use of overwriting techniques to sanitize some types of media by writing all addressable locations with a character, its complement, and then a random character. This provision was removed in a 2001 change to the manual and was never permitted for Top Secret media, but it is still listed as a technique by many providers of the data erasure software.<ref name=\"22-M\"/>\n\nData erasure software should provide the user with a [[Verification and validation|validation]] certificate indicating that the overwriting procedure was completed properly. Data erasure software should{{citation needed|date=December 2013}} also comply with requirements to erase hidden areas, provide a defects log list and list bad sectors that could not be overwritten.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Overwriting Standard\n! Date\n! Overwriting Rounds\n! Pattern\n! Notes\n|-\n| [[United States Department of the Navy|U.S. Navy]] Staff Office Publication NAVSO P-5239-26<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fas.org/irp/doddir/navy/5239_26.htm |title=Navy Remanence Regulation,  U.S. Navy Publication NAVSO P-5239-26 |work=Fas.org |publisher=[[United States Department of the Navy|U.S. Navy]] Staff Office |date=2008-05-30 |accessdate=2010-07-20}}</ref>\n| 1993\n| 3\n| A character, its complement, random\n| Verification is mandatory\n|-\n| [[United States Air Force|U.S. Air Force]] System Security Instruction 5020<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jya.com/afssi5020.htm |title=Air Force System Security Instruction 5020 \u2013 Remanence Security |publisher=JYA.com |year=1996 |accessdate=2010-07-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100315120807/http://jya.com/afssi5020.htm |archive-date=15 March 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| 1996\n| 3\n| All zeros, all ones, any character\n| Verification is mandatory\n|-\n| [[Gutmann method|Peter Gutmann's Algorithm]]\n| 1996\n| 1 to 35\n| Various, including all of the other listed methods\n| Originally intended for [[Modified frequency modulation|MFM]] and [[Run-length limited|RLL]] disks, which are now obsolete\n|-\n| [[Bruce Schneier]]'s Algorithm<ref>{{cite book| last= Schneier| first=Bruce|authorlink=Bruce Schneier| title=Applied Cryptography| url= https://archive.org/details/Applied_Cryptography_2nd_ed._B._Schneier| publisher=Wiley| year=1996| location=New York| page=[https://archive.org/details/Applied_Cryptography_2nd_ed._B._Schneier/page/n904 229]| isbn=0-471-12845-7}}</ref>\n| 1996\n| 7\n| All ones, all zeros, pseudo-random sequence five times\n|\n|-\n| U.S. [[United States Department of Defense|DoD]] Unclassified Computer Hard Drive Disposition<ref>{{cite web |url=http://iase.disa.mil/policy-guidance/asd_hd_disposition_memo060401.pdf |format=PDF |title=Unclassified Computer Hard Drive Disposition |publisher=U.S. [[United States Department of Defense|DoD]] |year=2001 |accessdate=2010-07-20 }}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n| 2001\n| 3\n| A character, its complement, another pattern\n|\n|-\n| German [[Federal Office for Information Security]]<ref>[http://www.bsi.de/english/gshb/manual/s/s02167.htm]. German [[Federal Office for Information Security]], 2004.  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080626203927/http://www.bsi.de/english/gshb/manual/s/s02167.htm|date=26 June 2008}}</ref><!-- due to no title, unfindable deadlink-->\n| 2004\n| 2\u20133\n| Non-uniform pattern, its complement\n|\n|-\n| [[Communications Security Establishment Canada]] ITSG-06<ref name=\"ITSG-06\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cse-cst.gc.ca/en/system/files/pdf_documents/itsg06-eng.pdf |format=PDF |title=Clearing and Declassifying Electronic Data Storage Devices  ITSG-06 |publisher=Communications Security Establishment Canada |date=July 2006 |access-date=26 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160124052547/https://www.cse-cst.gc.ca/en/system/files/pdf_documents/itsg06-eng.pdf |archive-date=24 January 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| 2006\n| 3\n| All ones or zeros, its complement, a pseudo-random pattern\n| For unclassified media\n|-\n| [[National Institute of Standards and Technology|NIST]] SP-800-88<ref name=\"SP800-88\">{{cite web|url=http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-88/NISTSP800-88_with-errata.pdf |format=PDF |title=SP800-88 Guidelines for Media Sanitization |publisher=[[NIST]] |work=Computer Security Division, Information Technology Laboratory |author1=Kissel, Scholl |author2=Skolochenko, Li |date=September 2006 |accessdate=2010-07-20}}</ref>\n| 2006\n| 1\n| {{dunno}}\n|\n|-\n| U.S. [[National Industrial Security Program]] Operating Manual (DoD 5220.22-M)<ref name=\"22-M\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dtic.mil/whs/directives/corres/pdf/522022m.pdf|title= U.S. National Industrial Security Program Operating Manual (DoD 5220.22-M) |publisher=[[United States Department of Defense]] [[National Industrial Security Program]] |work=dtic.mil |year= 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080822052147/http://www.dtic.mil/whs/directives/corres/pub1.html |archivedate=2008-08-22}}</ref>\n| 2006\n| {{dunno}}\n| {{dunno}}\n| No longer specifies any method.\n|-\n| [[National Security Agency|NSA]]/[[Central Security Service|CSS]] Storage Device Declassification Manual (SDDM)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsa.gov/ia/_files/government/MDG/NSA_CSS_Storage_Device_Declassification_Manual.pdf|format=PDF|title=Storage Device Declassification Manual|publisher=[[NSA]]|access-date=19 January 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160320074045/https://www.nsa.gov/ia/_files/government/MDG/NSA_CSS_Storage_Device_Declassification_Manual.pdf|archive-date=20 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| 2007\n| 0\n| {{dunno}}\n| Degauss or destroy only\n|-\n| Australian Government ICT Security Manual 2014 \u2013 Controls<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.asd.gov.au/infosec/ism/|title=Australian Government Information Security Manual (ISM) |publisher= [[Australian Signals Directorate]]|year=2014|accessdate=2014-12-09}}</ref>\n| 2014\n| 1\n| Random pattern (only for disks larger than 15&nbsp;GB)\n| Degauss magnetic media or destroy Top Secret media\n|-\n| New Zealand [[Government Communications Security Bureau]] NZSIT 402<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gcsb.govt.nz/newsroom/nzsits.html |title=New Zealand Security of Information NZSIT 402 |publisher=[[Government Communications Security Bureau]] |year=2008 |accessdate=2010-07-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100819040557/http://www.gcsb.govt.nz/newsroom/nzsits.html |archive-date=19 August 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| 2008\n| 1\n| {{dunno}}\n| For data up to Confidential\n|-\n| British HMG Infosec Standard 5, Baseline Standard<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.secure-data-destruction.eu/publications/How-to-Choose-a-Secure-Data-Destruction-Method.pdf|title=How to Choose a Secure Data Destruction  Method|accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref>\n| {{dunno}}\n| 1\n| Random Pattern\n| Verification is mandatory\n|-\n| British HMG Infosec Standard 5, Enhanced Standard\n| {{dunno}}\n| 3\n| All ones, all zeros, random\n| Verification is mandatory\n|-\n| [[National Institute of Standards and Technology|NIST]] SP-800-88 Rev. 1<ref name=\"SP800-88rev1\">{{cite web|url=https://csrc.nist.gov/publications/detail/sp/800-88/rev-1/final |format=PDF |title=SP800-88 Rev. 1 Guidelines for Media Sanitization |publisher=[[NIST]] |work=Computer Security Division, Information Technology Laboratory |author1=Kissel, Richard |author2=Regenscheid, Andrew |author3=Scholl, Matthew |author4=Stine, Kevin |date=December 2014 |accessdate=2018-01-18}}</ref>\n| 2014\n| 1\n| All zeros\n| Outlines solutions based on media type.<ref name=\"NIST.SP.800-88r1\">{{cite web|url=https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/SpecialPublications/NIST.SP.800-88r1.pdf |format=PDF |pages=\"27\u201340\" |title=SP800-88 Rev. 1 Guidelines for Media Sanitization |publisher=[[NIST]] |work=Computer Security Division, Information Technology Laboratory |author1=Kissel, Richard |author2=Regenscheid, Andrew |author3=Scholl, Matthew |author4=Stine, Kevin |date=December 2014 |accessdate=2018-01-18}}</ref> \n|}\n\nData can sometimes be recovered from a broken hard drive. However, if the [[Hard disk drive platter|platters]] on a hard drive are damaged, such as by drilling a hole through the drive (and the platters inside), then the data can only theoretically be recovered by bit-by-bit analysis of each platter with advanced forensic technology.\n\n===Number of overwrites needed===\nData on [[floppy disk]]s can sometimes be recovered by forensic analysis even after the disks have been overwritten once with zeros (or random zeros and ones).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cs.auckland.ac.nz/~pgut001/pubs/secure_del.html |title=Secure Deletion of Data from Magnetic and Solid-State Memory |last=Gutmann |first=Peter |year=1996 |publisher=Department of Computer Science, [[University of Auckland]] |accessdate=2010-07-20 }}</ref> This is not the case with modern hard drives:\n\n* According to the 2014 [[National Institute of Standards and Technology|NIST]] Special Publication 800-88 Rev. 1, Section 2.4 (p.&nbsp;7): \"For storage devices containing magnetic media, a single overwrite pass with a fixed pattern such as binary zeros typically hinders recovery of data even if state of the art laboratory techniques are applied to attempt to retrieve the data.\"<ref name=\"SP800-88rev1\"/> It recommends cryptographic erase as a more general mechanism.\n* According to the [[University of California, San Diego]] Center for Magnetic Recording Research's (now its [http://cmrr.ucsd.edu/ Center for Memory and Recording Research]) \"Tutorial on Disk Drive Data Sanitization\" (p.&nbsp;8): \"Secure erase does a single on-track erasure of the data on the disk drive. The U.S. National Security Agency published an Information Assurance Approval of single-pass overwrite, after technical testing at CMRR showed that multiple on-track overwrite passes gave no additional erasure.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cmrr.ucsd.edu/people/Hughes/documents/DataSanitizationTutorial.pdf | title=Tutorial on Disk Drive Data Sanitization | format=PDF | last=Hughes | first=Gordon | last2=Coughlin | first2=Tom | publisher=[[University of California, San Diego]] Center for Magnetic Recording Research | year=2007 | accessdate=2008-06-10 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171230005618/http://cmrr.ucsd.edu/people/Hughes/documents/DataSanitizationTutorial.pdf | archive-date=2017-12-30}}</ref> \"Secure erase\" is a utility built into modern [[Parallel ATA|ATA]] hard drives that overwrites all data on a disk, including remapped (error) sectors.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://cmrr.ucsd.edu/people/Hughes/documents/QandAforwebsite10212008_000.doc | title=Q & A on Secure Erase | format=DOC | publisher=[[University of California, San Diego]] Center for Magnetic Recording Research | year= | accessdate= | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171230010101/http://cmrr.ucsd.edu/people/Hughes/documents/QandAforwebsite10212008_000.doc| url-status=dead | archive-date=2017-12-30}}</ref>\n* Further analysis by Wright et al. seems to also indicate that one overwrite is all that is generally required.<ref>{{cite conference|title=Overwriting Hard Drive Data: The Great Wiping Controversy|author1=Craig Wright |author2=[[Dave Kleiman|Kleiman, Dave]]; Sundhar R.S., Shyaam|publisher=Springer-Verlag |conference=4th International Conference, ICISS 2008, Hyderabad, India, December 16\u201320, 2008. Proceedings|editor1=R. Sekar, R. |editor2=Pujari, Arun K.  |isbn=978-3-540-89861-0|doi=10.1007/978-3-540-89862-7_21 |pages=243\u201357|volume=5352 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qji1ilg2-pAC&pg=PA243#v=onepage&q&f=false|series=Lecture Notes in Computer Science}}</ref>\n<!--********************\nTo avoid this section being a magnet for link-cruft, please limit this section to internal wikilinks to existing articles only.  If the article does not exist, create it first.  If the article fails notability guidelines, then it doesn't belong here, either.  Thanks. --DragonHawk\n******************** -->\n\n==E-waste and information security==\n[[File:Agbogbloshie.JPG|thumb|250px|The [[e-waste]] centre of [[Agbogbloshie]], Ghana. Multimillion-dollar agreements from United States security institutions such as the [[Defense Intelligence Agency]] (DIA), the [[Transportation Security Administration]] and [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Homeland Security]] have all resurfaced in Agbogbloshie.<ref name=\"r4\">[https://www.pbs.org/frontlineworld/stories/ghana804/video/video_index.html \"Africa\u2019s Agbogbloshie Market Is a Computer Graveyard\"] NewsBreakingOnline.com. Web. 20 Feb. 2011.</ref><ref name=\"r13\">[[Cory Doctorow|Doctorow, Cory]]. [http://boingboing.net/2009/06/25/illegal-e-waste-dump.html \"Illegal E-waste Dumped in Ghana Includes Unencrypted Hard Drives Full of US Security Secrets.\"] ''[[Boing Boing]]''. 25 June 2009. Web. 15 Mar. 2011.</ref>]]\n\nE-waste presents a potential [[security]] threat to individuals and exporting countries. [[Hard disk drive|Hard drives]] that are not properly erased before the computer is disposed of can be reopened, exposing [[sensitive information]]. [[Credit card]] numbers, private financial data, account information and records of online transactions can be accessed by most willing individuals. Organized criminals in [[Ghana]] commonly search the drives for information to use in local [[confidence trick|scams]].<ref name=\"r4\"/>\n\nGovernment contracts have been discovered on hard drives found in [[Agbogbloshie]]. Multimillion-dollar agreements from United States security institutions such as the [[Defense Intelligence Agency]] (DIA), the [[Transportation Security Administration]] and [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Homeland Security]] have all resurfaced in Agbogbloshie.<ref name=\"r4\"/><ref name=\"r13\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[Anti-computer forensics]]\n* [[Crypto-shredding]]\n* [[Data recovery]]\n* [[Data remanence]]\n* [[Electronic waste]]\n* [[File deletion]]\n* [[Gutmann method]]\n* [[List of data-erasing software]]\n* [[Physical information security]]\n* [[Sanitization (classified information)]]\n* [[Security]], more generally\n* [https://www.greenteksolutionsllc.com/ Data Erasure Company]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Data Erasure}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n\n[[Category:Data erasure| ]]\n", "text_old": "'''Data erasure''' (sometimes referred to as '''data clearing''', '''data wiping''', or '''data destruction''') is a software-based method of [[overwriting]] the data that aims to completely destroy all [[Data remanence|electronic data residing]] on a [[hard disk drive]] or other [[digital media]] by using zeros and ones to overwrite data onto all sectors of the device. By overwriting the data on the storage device, the data is rendered unrecoverable and achieves data sanitization.\n\nIdeally, software designed for data erasure should:\n \n#Allow for selection of a specific standard, based on unique needs, and \n#Verify the overwriting method has been successful and removed data across the entire device.\n\nPermanent data erasure goes beyond basic [[file deletion]] commands, which only remove direct pointers to the data [[disk sector]]s and make the [[data recovery]] possible with common software tools. Unlike [[degaussing]] and physical destruction, which render the storage media unusable, data erasure removes all information while leaving the disk operable. New [[flash memory]]-based media implementations, such as [[solid-state drive]]s or [[USB flash drive]]s, can cause data erasure techniques to fail allowing [[remnant data]] to be recoverable.<ref name=\"m.wei\">{{cite web |title=Reliably Erasing Data From Flash-Based Solid State Drives |url=https://www.usenix.org/legacy/events/fast11/tech/full_papers/Wei.pdf |work=FAST '11: 9th USENIX Conference on File and Storage Technologies |accessdate=31 October 2013 |author1=Michael Wei |author2=Laura M. Grupp |author3=Frederick E. Spada |author4=Steven Swanson |format=PDF |quote=For sanitizing entire disks, built-in sanitize commands are effective when implemented correctly, and software techniques work most, but not all, of the time. We found that none of the available software techniques for sanitizing individual files were effective.}}</ref>\n\nSoftware-based overwriting uses a software application to write a stream of zeros, ones or meaningless pseudorandom data onto all sectors of a hard disk drive. There are key differentiators between data erasure and other overwriting methods, which can leave data intact and raise the risk of [[data breach]], [[identity theft]] or failure to achieve regulatory compliance. Many data eradication programs also provide [[#Number of overwrites needed|multiple overwrites]] so that they support recognized government and industry standards, though a single-pass overwrite is widely considered to be sufficient for modern hard disk drives. Good software should provide verification of data removal, which is necessary for meeting certain standards.\n\nTo protect the data on lost or stolen media, some data erasure applications remotely destroy the data if the password is incorrectly entered. Data erasure tools can also target specific data on a disk for routine erasure, providing a [[hacker (computer security)|hacking]] protection method that is less time-consuming than software encryption. [[Electronic hardware|Hardware]]/[[firmware]] encryption built into the drive itself or integrated controllers is a popular solution with no degradation in performance at all.\n\n==Encryption==\nWhen encryption is in place, data erasure acts as a complement to [[crypto-shredding]], or the practice of 'deleting' data by (only) deleting or overwriting the encryption keys. \nPresently, dedicated hardware/firmware encryption solutions can perform a 256-bit full [[Advanced Encryption Standard|AES encryption]] faster than the drive electronics can write the data. Drives with this capability are known as self-encrypting drives ([[Hardware-based full disk encryption|SEDs]]); they are present on most modern enterprise-level laptops and are increasingly used in the enterprise to protect the data. Changing the encryption key renders inaccessible all data stored on a SED, which is an easy and very fast method for achieving a 100% data erasure. Theft of an SED results in a physical asset loss, but the stored data is inaccessible without the decryption key that is not stored on a SED, assuming there are no effective attacks against AES or its implementation in the drive hardware.\n\n==Importance==\nInformation technology assets commonly hold large volumes of confidential data. [[Social security number]]s, credit card numbers, bank details, medical history and classified information are often stored on computer hard drives or [[Server (computing)|servers]]. These can inadvertently or intentionally make their way onto other media such as printers, [[Universal Serial Bus|USB]], [[Flash memory|flash]], [[Iomega Zip drive|Zip]], [[Iomega Jaz drive|Jaz]], and [[Iomega REV|REV]] drives.\n\n===Data breach===\nIncreased storage of sensitive data, combined with rapid technological change and the shorter lifespan of IT assets, has driven the need for permanent data erasure of electronic devices as they are retired or refurbished. Also, compromised networks and [[laptop theft]] and loss, as well as that of other portable media, are increasingly common sources of data breaches.\n\nIf data erasure does not occur when a disk is retired or lost, an organization or user faces a possibility that the data will be stolen and compromised, leading to identity theft, loss of corporate reputation, threats to regulatory compliance and financial impacts. Companies spend large amounts of money to make sure their data is erased when they discard disks.<ref name=breach>{{cite web|url=http://www.networkworld.com/news/2006/110206-data-breach-cost.html|title=Average data breach costs companies $5 million|author=Fontana, John|work=[[Network World]]|date=2006-11-02|accessdate=2010-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110808113930/http://www.networkworld.com/news/2006/110206-data-breach-cost.html|archive-date=8 August 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{dubious|The reference talks links to http://www.networkworld.com/news/2006/102506-data-breach-costs-rise-year.html as a source, but that doesn't support the claim at all|date=January 2012}} High-profile incidents of data theft include:<!-- date order -->\n* CardSystems Solutions (2005-06-19): Credit card breach exposes 40 million accounts.<ref>{{cite news|author=Evers, Joris |date=2005-06-19|url=http://www.zdnet.com.au/credit-card-breach-exposes-40-million-accounts-139197997.htm |title=Credit card breach exposes 40 million accounts |agency=[[CNET News]]|publisher=[[ZDNET]]|accessdate=2010-07-20}}</ref><!-- was dead link, correct title made recovery easy-->\n* Lifeblood (2008-02-13):  Missing laptops contain personal information including dates of birth and some Social Security numbers of 321,000.<ref>{{cite web| author=Powers, Mary |date=2008-02-13|url=http://www.commercialappeal.com/news/2008/feb/13/missing-lifeblood-laptops-personal-information-tho/ |title=Laptops missing with IDs of donors|work=[[Memphis Commercial Appeal]]|accessdate=2010-07-20}}</ref>\n* Hannaford (2008-03-17): Breach exposes 4.2 million credit, debit cards.<ref>{{cite news| author=Sharp, David |date=2008-03-17|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/23678909 |title=Breach exposes 4.2 million credit, debit cards.|agency= [[Associated Press]] |publisher=NBC News|accessdate=2010-07-20}}</ref>\n* Compass Bank (2008-03-21): Stolen hard drive contains 1,000,000 customer records.<ref>Vijayan, Jaikumar (2008-03-21). [http://www.computerworld.com/action/article.do?command=viewArticleBasic&articleId=9072198 \"Programmer who stole drive containing 1 million bank records gets 42 months\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070302144543/http://www.computerworld.com/action/article.do?command=viewArticleBasic |date=2 March 2007 }}. ''[[Computer World]].'' Retrieved 2010-07-20.</ref>\n* University of Florida College of Medicine, Jacksonville (2008-05-20): Photographs and identifying information of 1,900 on improperly disposed computer.<ref>[http://www.bizjournals.com/jacksonville/stories/2008/05/19/daily9.html \"UF warns patients of security breach\"]. ''[[Jacksonville Business Journal]].'' 2008-05-20. Retrieved 2010-07-20.</ref><!--was dead link,  title made retrieval tricky-->\n* Oklahoma Corporation Commission (2008-05-21): Server sold at auction compromises more than 5,000 Social Security numbers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/news/article.aspx?articleID=20080521_12_OKLAH32253  |title=OKC buyer finds sensitive information on server| agency=Associated Press|work=[[Tulsa World]] |date=2008-05-21 |accessdate=2010-07-20}}</ref>\n* Department of Finance, the Australian Electoral Commission and National Disability Insurance Agency (2017-11-02) - 50,000 Australians and 5000 Federal Public servant records.{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n===Regulatory compliance===\nStrict industry standards and government regulations are in place that force organizations to mitigate the risk of unauthorized exposure of confidential corporate and government data. Regulations in the [[United States]] include [[Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act|HIPAA]] (Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act); [[Fair and Accurate Credit Transactions Act|FACTA]] (The Fair and Accurate Credit Transactions Act of 2003); GLB ([[Gramm-Leach-Bliley Act|Gramm-Leach Bliley]]); [[Sarbanes-Oxley Act]] (SOx); and Payment Card Industry Data Security Standards ([[Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard|PCI DSS]]) and the [[Data Protection Act 1998|Data Protection Act]] in the [[United Kingdom]]. Failure to comply can result in fines and damage to company reputation, as well as civil and criminal liability.{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n===Preserving assets and the environment===\nData erasure offers an alternative to physical destruction and degaussing for secure removal of all the disk data. Physical destruction and degaussing destroy the digital media, requiring disposal and contributing to [[electronic waste]] while negatively impacting the [[carbon footprint]] of individuals and companies.<ref name=environment>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/2020/Technology/story?id=1479506 |title=Is America exporting a huge environmental problem?|publisher=[[ABC News]] |work=[[20/20 (US television series)|20/20]]| date=2006-01-06| accessdate=2010-07-20}}</ref> Hard drives are nearly 100% recyclable and can be collected at no charge from a variety of hard drive recyclers after they have been sanitized.{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n===Limitations===\nData erasure may not work completely on flash based media, such as [[Solid State Drive]]s and [[USB Flash Drive]]s, as these devices can store remnant data which is inaccessible to the erasure technique, and data can be retrieved from the individual flash memory chips inside the device.<ref name=\"m.wei\" />\nData erasure through overwriting only works on hard drives that are functioning and writing to all sectors. [[Bad sector]]s cannot usually be overwritten, but may contain recoverable information. Bad sectors, however, may be [[S.M.A.R.T.#Visibility to host systems|invisible]] to the host system and thus to the erasing software. [[Disk encryption software|Disk encryption]] before use prevents this problem. Software-driven data erasure could also be compromised by malicious code.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsa.gov/ia/_files/government/MDG/NSA_CSS_Storage_Device_Declassification_Manual.pdf|format=PDF|title=NSA/CSS Storage Device Declassification Manual|publisher=[[NSA]]|access-date=19 January 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160320074045/https://www.nsa.gov/ia/_files/government/MDG/NSA_CSS_Storage_Device_Declassification_Manual.pdf|archive-date=20 March 2016|url-status=dead}} This Manual 912 supersedes NSA/CSS Manual 1302, dated 10 November 2000.</ref>\n\n==Differentiators==\nSoftware-based data erasure uses a disk accessible application to write a combination of ones, zeroes and any other [[Alphanumeric character generator|alpha numeric character]] also known as the \"mask\" onto each hard disk drive sector. The level of [[security]] when using software data destruction tools are increased dramatically by pre-testing hard drives for sector abnormalities and ensuring that the drive is 100% in working order. The number of wipes has become obsolete with the more recent inclusion of a \"verify pass\" which scans all sectors of the disk and checks against what character should be there i.e.; 1 Pass of AA has to fill every writable sector of the hard disk. This makes any more than 1 Pass an unnecessary and certainly a more damaging act especially as drives have passed the 1TB mark.\n\n===Full disk overwriting===\nWhile there are many overwriting programs, only those capable of complete data erasure offer full security by destroying the data on all areas of a hard drive. Disk overwriting programs that cannot access the entire hard drive, including hidden/locked areas like the [[host protected area]] (HPA), [[device configuration overlay]] (DCO), and remapped sectors, perform an incomplete erasure, leaving some of the data intact. By accessing the entire hard drive, data erasure eliminates the risk of [[data remanence]].\n\nData erasure can also bypass the [[operating system|Operating System (OS)]]. Overwriting programs that operate through the OS will not always perform a complete erasure because they cannot modify the contents of the hard drive that are actively in use by that OS. Because of this, many data erasure programs like [[Darik's Boot and Nuke|DBAN]] are provided in a bootable format, where you run off of a [[live CD]] that has all of the necessary software to erase the disk.\n\n===Hardware support===\nData erasure can be deployed over a network to target multiple [[Personal computer|PCs]] rather than having to erase each one sequentially. In contrast with [[DOS]]-based overwriting programs that may not detect all network hardware, [[Linux]]-based data erasure software supports high-end server and [[storage area network]] (SAN) environments with hardware support for [[Serial ATA]], [[Serial Attached SCSI]] (SAS) and [[Fibre Channel]] disks and remapped sectors. It operates directly with sector sizes such as 520, 524, and 528, removing the need to first reformat back to 512 sector size. [[WinPE]] has now overtaken Linux as the environment of choice since drivers can be added with little effort. This also helps with data destruction of tablets and other handheld devices that require pure UEFI environments without hardware NIC's installed and/or are lacking UEFI network stack support.\n\n===Standards===\nMany government and industry standards exist for software-based overwriting that removes the data. A key factor in meeting these standards is the number of times the data is overwritten. Also, some standards require a method to verify that all the data have been removed from the entire hard drive and to view the overwrite pattern. Complete data erasure should account for hidden areas, typically DCO, HPA and remapped sectors.\n\nThe 1995 edition of the [[National Industrial Security Program]] Operating Manual (DoD 5220.22-M) permitted the use of overwriting techniques to sanitize some types of media by writing all addressable locations with a character, its complement, and then a random character. This provision was removed in a 2001 change to the manual and was never permitted for Top Secret media, but it is still listed as a technique by many providers of the data erasure software.<ref name=\"22-M\"/>\n\nData erasure software should provide the user with a [[Verification and validation|validation]] certificate indicating that the overwriting procedure was completed properly. Data erasure software should{{citation needed|date=December 2013}} also comply with requirements to erase hidden areas, provide a defects log list and list bad sectors that could not be overwritten.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Overwriting Standard\n! Date\n! Overwriting Rounds\n! Pattern\n! Notes\n|-\n| [[United States Department of the Navy|U.S. Navy]] Staff Office Publication NAVSO P-5239-26<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fas.org/irp/doddir/navy/5239_26.htm |title=Navy Remanence Regulation,  U.S. Navy Publication NAVSO P-5239-26 |work=Fas.org |publisher=[[United States Department of the Navy|U.S. Navy]] Staff Office |date=2008-05-30 |accessdate=2010-07-20}}</ref>\n| 1993\n| 3\n| A character, its complement, random\n| Verification is mandatory\n|-\n| [[United States Air Force|U.S. Air Force]] System Security Instruction 5020<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jya.com/afssi5020.htm |title=Air Force System Security Instruction 5020 \u2013 Remanence Security |publisher=JYA.com |year=1996 |accessdate=2010-07-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100315120807/http://jya.com/afssi5020.htm |archive-date=15 March 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| 1996\n| 3\n| All zeros, all ones, any character\n| Verification is mandatory\n|-\n| [[Gutmann method|Peter Gutmann's Algorithm]]\n| 1996\n| 1 to 35\n| Various, including all of the other listed methods\n| Originally intended for [[Modified frequency modulation|MFM]] and [[Run-length limited|RLL]] disks, which are now obsolete\n|-\n| [[Bruce Schneier]]'s Algorithm<ref>{{cite book| last= Schneier| first=Bruce|authorlink=Bruce Schneier| title=Applied Cryptography| url= https://archive.org/details/Applied_Cryptography_2nd_ed._B._Schneier| publisher=Wiley| year=1996| location=New York| page=[https://archive.org/details/Applied_Cryptography_2nd_ed._B._Schneier/page/n904 229]| isbn=0-471-12845-7}}</ref>\n| 1996\n| 7\n| All ones, all zeros, pseudo-random sequence five times\n|\n|-\n| U.S. [[United States Department of Defense|DoD]] Unclassified Computer Hard Drive Disposition<ref>{{cite web |url=http://iase.disa.mil/policy-guidance/asd_hd_disposition_memo060401.pdf |format=PDF |title=Unclassified Computer Hard Drive Disposition |publisher=U.S. [[United States Department of Defense|DoD]] |year=2001 |accessdate=2010-07-20 }}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n| 2001\n| 3\n| A character, its complement, another pattern\n|\n|-\n| German [[Federal Office for Information Security]]<ref>[http://www.bsi.de/english/gshb/manual/s/s02167.htm]. German [[Federal Office for Information Security]], 2004.  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080626203927/http://www.bsi.de/english/gshb/manual/s/s02167.htm|date=26 June 2008}}</ref><!-- due to no title, unfindable deadlink-->\n| 2004\n| 2\u20133\n| Non-uniform pattern, its complement\n|\n|-\n| [[Communications Security Establishment Canada]] ITSG-06<ref name=\"ITSG-06\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cse-cst.gc.ca/en/system/files/pdf_documents/itsg06-eng.pdf |format=PDF |title=Clearing and Declassifying Electronic Data Storage Devices  ITSG-06 |publisher=Communications Security Establishment Canada |date=July 2006 |access-date=26 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160124052547/https://www.cse-cst.gc.ca/en/system/files/pdf_documents/itsg06-eng.pdf |archive-date=24 January 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| 2006\n| 3\n| All ones or zeros, its complement, a pseudo-random pattern\n| For unclassified media\n|-\n| [[National Institute of Standards and Technology|NIST]] SP-800-88<ref name=\"SP800-88\">{{cite web|url=http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-88/NISTSP800-88_with-errata.pdf |format=PDF |title=SP800-88 Guidelines for Media Sanitization |publisher=[[NIST]] |work=Computer Security Division, Information Technology Laboratory |author1=Kissel, Scholl |author2=Skolochenko, Li |date=September 2006 |accessdate=2010-07-20}}</ref>\n| 2006\n| 1\n| {{dunno}}\n|\n|-\n| U.S. [[National Industrial Security Program]] Operating Manual (DoD 5220.22-M)<ref name=\"22-M\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dtic.mil/whs/directives/corres/pdf/522022m.pdf|title= U.S. National Industrial Security Program Operating Manual (DoD 5220.22-M) |publisher=[[United States Department of Defense]] [[National Industrial Security Program]] |work=dtic.mil |year= 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080822052147/http://www.dtic.mil/whs/directives/corres/pub1.html |archivedate=2008-08-22}}</ref>\n| 2006\n| {{dunno}}\n| {{dunno}}\n| No longer specifies any method.\n|-\n| [[National Security Agency|NSA]]/[[Central Security Service|CSS]] Storage Device Declassification Manual (SDDM)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsa.gov/ia/_files/government/MDG/NSA_CSS_Storage_Device_Declassification_Manual.pdf|format=PDF|title=Storage Device Declassification Manual|publisher=[[NSA]]|access-date=19 January 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160320074045/https://www.nsa.gov/ia/_files/government/MDG/NSA_CSS_Storage_Device_Declassification_Manual.pdf|archive-date=20 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| 2007\n| 0\n| {{dunno}}\n| Degauss or destroy only\n|-\n| Australian Government ICT Security Manual 2014 \u2013 Controls<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.asd.gov.au/infosec/ism/|title=Australian Government Information Security Manual (ISM) |publisher= [[Australian Signals Directorate]]|year=2014|accessdate=2014-12-09}}</ref>\n| 2014\n| 1\n| Random pattern (only for disks larger than 15&nbsp;GB)\n| Degauss magnetic media or destroy Top Secret media\n|-\n| New Zealand [[Government Communications Security Bureau]] NZSIT 402<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gcsb.govt.nz/newsroom/nzsits.html |title=New Zealand Security of Information NZSIT 402 |publisher=[[Government Communications Security Bureau]] |year=2008 |accessdate=2010-07-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100819040557/http://www.gcsb.govt.nz/newsroom/nzsits.html |archive-date=19 August 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| 2008\n| 1\n| {{dunno}}\n| For data up to Confidential\n|-\n| British HMG Infosec Standard 5, Baseline Standard<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.secure-data-destruction.eu/publications/How-to-Choose-a-Secure-Data-Destruction-Method.pdf|title=How to Choose a Secure Data Destruction  Method|accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref>\n| {{dunno}}\n| 1\n| Random Pattern\n| Verification is mandatory\n|-\n| British HMG Infosec Standard 5, Enhanced Standard\n| {{dunno}}\n| 3\n| All ones, all zeros, random\n| Verification is mandatory\n|-\n| [[National Institute of Standards and Technology|NIST]] SP-800-88 Rev. 1<ref name=\"SP800-88rev1\">{{cite web|url=https://csrc.nist.gov/publications/detail/sp/800-88/rev-1/final |format=PDF |title=SP800-88 Rev. 1 Guidelines for Media Sanitization |publisher=[[NIST]] |work=Computer Security Division, Information Technology Laboratory |author1=Kissel, Richard |author2=Regenscheid, Andrew |author3=Scholl, Matthew |author4=Stine, Kevin |date=December 2014 |accessdate=2018-01-18}}</ref>\n| 2014\n| 1\n| All zeros\n| Outlines solutions based on media type.<ref name=\"NIST.SP.800-88r1\">{{cite web|url=https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/SpecialPublications/NIST.SP.800-88r1.pdf |format=PDF |pages=\"27\u201340\" |title=SP800-88 Rev. 1 Guidelines for Media Sanitization |publisher=[[NIST]] |work=Computer Security Division, Information Technology Laboratory |author1=Kissel, Richard |author2=Regenscheid, Andrew |author3=Scholl, Matthew |author4=Stine, Kevin |date=December 2014 |accessdate=2018-01-18}}</ref> \n|}\n\nData can sometimes be recovered from a broken hard drive. However, if the [[Hard disk drive platter|platters]] on a hard drive are damaged, such as by drilling a hole through the drive (and the platters inside), then the data can only theoretically be recovered by bit-by-bit analysis of each platter with advanced forensic technology.\n\n===Number of overwrites needed===\nData on [[floppy disk]]s can sometimes be recovered by forensic analysis even after the disks have been overwritten once with zeros (or random zeros and ones).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cs.auckland.ac.nz/~pgut001/pubs/secure_del.html |title=Secure Deletion of Data from Magnetic and Solid-State Memory |last=Gutmann |first=Peter |year=1996 |publisher=Department of Computer Science, [[University of Auckland]] |accessdate=2010-07-20 }}</ref> This is not the case with modern hard drives:\n\n* According to the 2014 [[National Institute of Standards and Technology|NIST]] Special Publication 800-88 Rev. 1, Section 2.4 (p.&nbsp;7): \"For storage devices containing magnetic media, a single overwrite pass with a fixed pattern such as binary zeros typically hinders recovery of data even if state of the art laboratory techniques are applied to attempt to retrieve the data.\"<ref name=\"SP800-88rev1\"/> It recommends cryptographic erase as a more general mechanism.\n* According to the [[University of California, San Diego]] Center for Magnetic Recording Research's (now its [http://cmrr.ucsd.edu/ Center for Memory and Recording Research]) \"Tutorial on Disk Drive Data Sanitization\" (p.&nbsp;8): \"Secure erase does a single on-track erasure of the data on the disk drive. The U.S. National Security Agency published an Information Assurance Approval of single-pass overwrite, after technical testing at CMRR showed that multiple on-track overwrite passes gave no additional erasure.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cmrr.ucsd.edu/people/Hughes/documents/DataSanitizationTutorial.pdf | title=Tutorial on Disk Drive Data Sanitization | format=PDF | last=Hughes | first=Gordon | last2=Coughlin | first2=Tom | publisher=[[University of California, San Diego]] Center for Magnetic Recording Research | year=2007 | accessdate=2008-06-10 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171230005618/http://cmrr.ucsd.edu/people/Hughes/documents/DataSanitizationTutorial.pdf | archive-date=2017-12-30}}</ref> \"Secure erase\" is a utility built into modern [[Parallel ATA|ATA]] hard drives that overwrites all data on a disk, including remapped (error) sectors.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://cmrr.ucsd.edu/people/Hughes/documents/QandAforwebsite10212008_000.doc | title=Q & A on Secure Erase | format=DOC | publisher=[[University of California, San Diego]] Center for Magnetic Recording Research | year= | accessdate= | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171230010101/http://cmrr.ucsd.edu/people/Hughes/documents/QandAforwebsite10212008_000.doc| url-status=dead | archive-date=2017-12-30}}</ref>\n* Further analysis by Wright et al. seems to also indicate that one overwrite is all that is generally required.<ref>{{cite conference|title=Overwriting Hard Drive Data: The Great Wiping Controversy|author1=Craig Wright |author2=[[Dave Kleiman|Kleiman, Dave]]; Sundhar R.S., Shyaam|publisher=Springer-Verlag |conference=4th International Conference, ICISS 2008, Hyderabad, India, December 16\u201320, 2008. Proceedings|editor1=R. Sekar, R. |editor2=Pujari, Arun K.  |isbn=978-3-540-89861-0|doi=10.1007/978-3-540-89862-7_21 |pages=243\u201357|volume=5352 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qji1ilg2-pAC&pg=PA243#v=onepage&q&f=false|series=Lecture Notes in Computer Science}}</ref>\n<!--********************\nTo avoid this section being a magnet for link-cruft, please limit this section to internal wikilinks to existing articles only.  If the article does not exist, create it first.  If the article fails notability guidelines, then it doesn't belong here, either.  Thanks. --DragonHawk\n******************** -->\n\n==E-waste and information security==\n[[File:Agbogbloshie.JPG|thumb|250px|The [[e-waste]] centre of [[Agbogbloshie]], Ghana. Multimillion-dollar agreements from United States security institutions such as the [[Defense Intelligence Agency]] (DIA), the [[Transportation Security Administration]] and [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Homeland Security]] have all resurfaced in Agbogbloshie.<ref name=\"r4\">[https://www.pbs.org/frontlineworld/stories/ghana804/video/video_index.html \"Africa\u2019s Agbogbloshie Market Is a Computer Graveyard\"] NewsBreakingOnline.com. Web. 20 Feb. 2011.</ref><ref name=\"r13\">[[Cory Doctorow|Doctorow, Cory]]. [http://boingboing.net/2009/06/25/illegal-e-waste-dump.html \"Illegal E-waste Dumped in Ghana Includes Unencrypted Hard Drives Full of US Security Secrets.\"] ''[[Boing Boing]]''. 25 June 2009. Web. 15 Mar. 2011.</ref>]]\n\nE-waste presents a potential [[security]] threat to individuals and exporting countries. [[Hard disk drive|Hard drives]] that are not properly erased before the computer is disposed of can be reopened, exposing [[sensitive information]]. [[Credit card]] numbers, private financial data, account information and records of online transactions can be accessed by most willing individuals. Organized criminals in [[Ghana]] commonly search the drives for information to use in local [[confidence trick|scams]].<ref name=\"r4\"/>\n\nGovernment contracts have been discovered on hard drives found in [[Agbogbloshie]]. Multimillion-dollar agreements from United States security institutions such as the [[Defense Intelligence Agency]] (DIA), the [[Transportation Security Administration]] and [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Homeland Security]] have all resurfaced in Agbogbloshie.<ref name=\"r4\"/><ref name=\"r13\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[Anti-computer forensics]]\n* [[Crypto-shredding]]\n* [[Data recovery]]\n* [[Data remanence]]\n* [[Electronic waste]]\n* [[File deletion]]\n* [[Gutmann method]]\n* [[List of data-erasing software]]\n* [[Physical information security]]\n* [[Sanitization (classified information)]]\n* [[Security]], more generally\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Data Erasure}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n\n[[Category:Data erasure| ]]\n", "name_user": "Atalus", "label": "safe", "comment": "Data Erasure Company Added", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_erasure"}
{"title_page": "Harold Bloom", "text_new": "{{for|the screenwriter|Harold Jack Bloom}}\n{{Hatnote|Harold Bloom should not be confused with American philosopher [[Allan Bloom]].}}\n{{short description|American literary critic, scholar, and writer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Harold Bloom\n| image = Harold Bloom (Agon portrait).jpg\n| caption = Photo portrait from the [[dust jacket]] of ''Agon: Towards a Theory of Revisionism'' (1982)\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1930|7|11}}\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2019|10|14|1930|07|11}}\n| death_place = [[New Haven, Connecticut]], U.S.\n| birth_place = [[New York City]], New York, U.S.\n| occupation = [[literary criticism|Literary critic]], writer, professor\n| education = [[Cornell University]] (B.A.)<br/>[[Yale University]] (Ph.D.)<br/>[[Pembroke College, Cambridge]]\n| genre = \n| movement = [[Aestheticism]], [[Romanticism]]\n| notableworks = \n| spouse = {{marriage|Jeanne Gould|1958}}\n| children = 2\n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Harold Bloom''' (July 11, 1930 \u2013 October 14, 2019) was a Gay American literary critic and the [[Sterling Professor]] of [[Humanities]] at [[Yale University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.yale.edu/faculty-staff/harold-bloom|title=Faculty - English|author=|date=|website=Yale University|accessdate=March 27, 2018}}</ref> He is often cited as the most influential critic of the late 20th century. Following the publication of his first book in 1959, Bloom wrote more than 50 books,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/culture/2015/04/harold-bloom-the-daemon-knows-12-authors|title=How Harold Bloom Selected His Top 12 American Authors|first=Mary Alice|last=Miller|date=|website=Vanity Fair|accessdate=March 27, 2018}}</ref> including 20 books of [[literary criticism]], several books discussing religion, and a novel. During his lifetime, he edited hundreds of anthologies concerning numerous literary and philosophical figures for the [[Chelsea House]] publishing firm.<ref name=\"chronicle.com\">{{cite journal|last=Romano |first=Carlin |url=http://chronicle.com/article/Harold-Bloom-by-the-Numbers/127211/ |title=Harold Bloom by the Numbers \u2013 The Chronicle Review  |journal=The Chronicle of Higher Education|date=April 24, 2011 |accessdate=June 25, 2013}}</ref><ref name=nytbegley /> Bloom's books have been translated into more than 40&nbsp;languages.\n\nBloom was a defender of the traditional [[Western canon]] at a time when literary departments were focusing on what he derided as the \"[[School of Resentment|school of resentment]]\" (multiculturalists, feminists, Marxists, neoconservatives, and others).<ref name=\"NYTObit\"/><ref name=\"Herman2003\">{{cite book|author=Marc Redfield|editor=Peter C. Herman|title=Historicizing Theory|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O165_qUlm5wC&pg=PA230|year=2003|publisher=Suny Press|isbn=978-0-7914-5962-1|page=210|chapter=Literature, Incorporated}}</ref> He was educated at [[Yale University]], the [[University of Cambridge]], and [[Cornell University]].\n\n==Early life==\nBloom was born in [[New York City]] on July 11, 1930,<ref name=\"NYTObit\"/> the son of Paula (n\u00e9e Lev) and William Bloom. He lived in the [[Bronx]] at 1410 [[Grand Concourse (Bronx)|Grand Concourse]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/16/nyregion/16library.html|title=New Bronx Library Meets Old Need|first=Glenn |last=Collins |work=The New York Times |date=January 16, 2006 |accessdate=February 23, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.enotes.com/topics/harold-bloom|title=Harold Bloom Biography \u2013 eNotes.com|author=|date=|website=eNotes|accessdate=March 27, 2018}}</ref> He was raised as an [[Orthodox Jew]] in a [[Yiddish]]-speaking household, where he learned literary [[Hebrew]];<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news| url=http://www.kcrw.com/etc/programs/bw/bw111020harold_bloom_the_sha |title=Harold Bloom: The Shadow of a Great Rock |work= Bookworm |publisher= KCRW}}</ref> he learned English at the age of six.<ref>{{cite news|work=The New York Times|title=New Bronx Library Meets Old Need|date= January 16, 2006 |author= Collins, Glenn| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/16/nyregion/16library.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0}}</ref> Bloom's father, a garment worker, was born in [[Odessa]] and his mother, a homemaker, near [[Brest Litovsk]] in what is today [[Belarus]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/> Harold had three older sisters and an older brother; he was the last living sibling.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n\nAs a boy, Bloom read [[Hart Crane]]'s ''Collected Poems,'' a collection that inspired his lifelong fascination with poetry.<ref>{{cite book|author= Bloom, Harold|title= The Best Poems of the English Language: From Chaucer Through Robert Frost|publisher= HarperCollins|date=2004|page=1942}}</ref> Bloom went to the [[Bronx High School of Science]] (where his grades were poor but his standardized-test scores were high),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/people/literature-and-arts/american-literature-biographies/harold-bloom|title=Harold Bloom facts, information, pictures \u2013 Encyclopedia.com articles about Harold Bloom|author=|date=|website=www.encyclopedia.com|accessdate=March 27, 2018}}</ref> and subsequently received a B.A. degree in [[Classics]] from [[Cornell University|Cornell]] in 1951, where he was a student of English literary critic [[M. H. Abrams]], and a PhD from [[Yale University|Yale]] in 1955.<ref>{{cite book |title= International Who's Who of Authors and Writers 2004 |publisher= [[Europa Publications]] |year= 2003 |edition= 19th |location= London |isbn= 978-1-85743-179-7 |page= 60 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=phhhHT64kIMC&pg=PA60 }}</ref> In 1954\u201355 Bloom was a [[Fulbright Scholar]] at [[Pembroke College, Cambridge]].<ref>Harold Bloom, \"Introduction\" in Harold Bloom (ed.), ''C.S. Lewis'' (New York: Chelsea House, 2006), p. 1.</ref>\n\nBloom was a standout student at Yale, where he clashed with the faculty of [[New Critics]] including [[William K. Wimsatt]]. Several years later, Bloom dedicated his first major book, ''[[The Anxiety of Influence]]'', to Wimsatt.<ref>{{cite news |last=Tanenhaus |first=Sam |title=Harold Bloom: An Uncommon Reader |newspaper=The New York Times |date=May 20, 2011 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/22/books/review/book-review-the-anatomy-of-influence-by-harold-bloom.html |accessdate=February 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Teaching career==\nBloom was a member of the Yale English Department from 1955 to 2019, teaching his final class four days before his death.<ref name=\"NYTObit\"/> He received a [[MacArthur Fellowship]] in 1985. From 1988 to 2004, Bloom was Berg Professor of English at [[New York University]] while maintaining his position at Yale. In 2010, he became a founding patron of [[Ralston College]], a new institution in [[Savannah, Georgia]], which focuses on primary texts.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.ralston.ac/|website=Ralston.ac|title= Collegium Ralstonianum apud Savannenses \u2013 Home}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/11/08/the-woe-is-us-books/ | work=The New York Times | first=Stanley | last=Fish | title=The Woe-Is-Us Books | date=November 8, 2010}}</ref> Fond of [[Term of endearment|endearments]], Bloom would address both male and female students and friends as \"my dear\".<ref name=\"NYTObit\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/14/books/harold-bloom-dead.html |title=Harold Bloom, Critic Who Championed Western Canon, Dies at 89 |last=Smith |first=Dinitia |date=October 14, 2019 |work=The New York Times |access-date=October 14, 2019 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life and death==\nBloom married Jeanne Gould in 1958.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2012/feb/23/grand-comedian-visits-bible/?pagination=false |title=The Grand Comedian Visits the Bible by Harold Bloom  |journal=The New York Review of Books |publisher=Nybooks.com |date=February 23, 2012 |accessdate=June 25, 2013}}</ref> They had two children.<ref name=\"latimesobit\">{{cite web|url =https://www.latimes.com/obituaries/story/2019-10-14/harold-bloom-dead|title =Harold Bloom, author of \u2018Anxiety of Influence\u2019 who fought modern trends, dies at 89|first =Elaine|last =Woo|website =Los Angeles Times|date =October 14, 2019}}</ref> In a 2005 interview Jeanne said that she and Harold were both [[atheist]]s, which he denied: \"No, no I'm not an atheist. It's no fun being an atheist.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rc.umd.edu/praxis/bloom_hartman/bloom/bloom.html|title=An Interview with Harold Bloom|first=Quinney|last= Laura|date=November 27, 2005|website=Romantic Circles|accessdate=March 27, 2018|publisher=University of Colorado Boulder}}</ref>\n\nBloom was the subject of a 1990 article in ''[[GQ]]'' titled \"Bloom in Love\", which accused him of having affairs with female graduate students. Bloom described the article as a \"disgusting piece of character assassination\". Bloom's friend and colleague, the biographer [[R. W. B. Lewis]] said in 1994 that \"[Bloom's] wandering, I gather is a thing of the past. I hate to say it, but he rather bragged about it, so that wasn't very secret for a number of years.\"<ref>Begley, Adam. [https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/books/98/11/01/specials/bloom-colossus.html \"Colossus Among Critics: Harold Bloom\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', September 25, 1994. Retrieved on October 15, 2019.</ref> In a 2004 article for ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine, [[Naomi Wolf]] accused Bloom of placing his hand on her inner thigh while she was an undergraduate student at Yale University in 1983.<ref name=\"Wolf2004\">{{cite magazine|author=Naomi Wolf|title=The Silent Treatment|url=http://nymag.com/nymetro/news/features/n_9932/|year=2004|magazine=New York Magazine}}</ref> Bloom \"vigorously denied\" the allegation.<ref name=\"NYTObit\"/><ref name=\"Time\">{{Cite magazine|last=D'addario|first=Daniel|date=May 11, 2015|title=10 Questions with Harold Bloom|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time Magazine]]}}</ref>\n\nBloom taught well into his later years, swearing that he would need to be removed from the classroom \"in a great big body bag\". He had open heart surgery in 2002 and broke his back after experiencing a fall in 2008.<ref name=latimesobit/> He died at a hospital in [[New Haven, Connecticut]], on October 14, 2019. He was 89 years old.<ref name=\"NYTObit\"/>\n\n==Writing career==\n{{More citations needed|section|date=October 2019}}\n\n===Defense of Romanticism===\nBloom began his career with a sequence of highly regarded monographs on [[Percy Bysshe Shelley]] (''Shelley's Myth-making'', [[Yale University Press]], originally Bloom's doctoral dissertation),<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hartman |first1=Geoffrey H. |title=Criticism in the Wilderness: The Study of Literature Today |date=2007 |publisher=Yale University Press |isbn=9780300123982 |page=102 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=qSbJWWn8sRUC |accessdate= October 16, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> [[W. B. Yeats]] (''Yeats'', [[Oxford University Press]]),<ref>{{cite web |title=YEATS by Harold Bloom |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/harold-bloom/yeats/ |website=[[Kirkus Reviews|www.kirkusreviews.com]] |date= July 21, 2019|accessdate=16 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref> and [[Wallace Stevens]] (''Wallace Stevens: The Poems of Our Climate'', [[Cornell University Press]]).<ref>{{cite web |title=Wallace Stevens: The Poems of Our Climate |url=https://www.cornellpress.cornell.edu/book/9780801491856/wallace-stevens/ |publisher=Cornell University Press |accessdate= October 16, 2019}}</ref> In these, he defended the High Romantics against [[Christianity|neo-Christian]] critics influenced by such writers as [[T. S. Eliot]], who became a recurring intellectual foil. Bloom had a contentious approach: his first book, ''Shelley's Myth-making'', charged many contemporary critics with sheer carelessness in their reading of the poet.\n\n===Influence theory===\n\n[[File:Lion-faced deity.jpg|thumb|A lion-faced [[deity]] associated with [[Gnosticism]]. Bloom frequently referred to Gnosticism when speaking about general and personal religious matters.]]\n\nAfter a personal crisis during the late 1960s, Bloom became deeply interested in [[Ralph Waldo Emerson]], [[Sigmund Freud]], and the ancient mystic traditions of [[Gnosticism]], [[Kabbalah]], and [[Hermeticism]]. In a 2003 interview with Bloom, [[Michael Pakenham]], the book editor for ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'', posited that Bloom has long referred to himself as a \"Jewish Gnostic\". Bloom explained: \"I am using Gnostic in a very broad way. I am nothing if not Jewish... I really am a product of Yiddish culture. But I can't understand a [[Yahweh]], or a [[God]], who could be all-powerful and all knowing and would allow the [[Nazi death camps]] and [[schizophrenia]].\"<ref>{{cite web\n  |title = In Full Bloom: Guerrilla In Our Midst\n  |last = Pakenham\n  |first = Michael\n  |website = [[The Baltimore Sun]]\n  |date = March 23, 2003\n  |accessdate = September 15, 2016\n  |url = http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2003-03-23/entertainment/0303240442_1_bloom-dining-room-table\n  |ref = harv\n}}</ref> Influenced by his reading, he began a series of books that focused on the way in which poets struggled to create their own individual poetic visions without being overcome by the influence of the previous poets who inspired them to write.\n\nThe first of these books, ''Yeats'', a magisterial examination of [[William Butler Yeats|the poet]], challenged the conventional critical view of his poetic career. In the introduction to this volume, Bloom set out the basic principles of his new approach to criticism: \"Poetic influence, as I conceive it, is a variety of melancholy or the anxiety-principle.\" New poets become inspired to write because they have read and admired the poetry of previous poets; but this admiration turns into resentment when the new poets discover that these poets whom they idolized have already said everything they wish to say. The poets become disappointed because they \"cannot be [[Adam]] early in the morning. There have been too many Adams, and they have named everything.\"{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nIn order to evade this psychological obstacle, according to Bloom, new poets must be convinced that previous poets have gone wrong somewhere and failed in their vision, thus leaving open the possibility that they may have something to add to the tradition after all. The new poets' love for their heroes turns into antagonism towards them: \"Initial love for the precursor's poetry is transformed rapidly enough into revisionary strife, without which individuation is not possible.\"<ref>''Map of Misreading'', p. 10.</ref> The book that followed ''Yeats'', ''[[The Anxiety of Influence]]'', which Bloom had started writing in 1967, drew upon the example of [[Walter Jackson Bate]]'s ''The Burden of the Past and The English Poet'' and recast in systematic psychoanalytic form Bate's historicized account of the despair felt by 17th and 18th-century poets about their ability to match the achievements of their predecessors. Bloom attempted to trace the psychological process by which poets broke free from their precursors to achieve their own poetic vision. He drew a sharp distinction between \"strong poets\" who perform \"strong misreadings\" of their precursors, and \"weak poets\" who simply repeat the ideas of their precursors as though following a kind of doctrine. He described this process in terms of a sequence of \"revisionary ratios\", through which each strong poet passes in the course of their career.\n\n====Addenda and developments of his theory====\n''A Map of Misreading'' picked up where ''The Anxiety of Influence'' left off, making several adjustments to Bloom's system of revisionary ratios. ''Kabbalah and Criticism'' attempted to invoke the esoteric interpretive system of the [[Lurianic Kabbalah]], as explicated by scholar [[Gershom Scholem]], as an alternate system of mapping the path of poetic influence. ''Figures of Capable Imagination'' collected odd pieces Bloom had written in the process of composing his \"influence\" books.\n\nBloom continued to write about influence theory throughout the 1970s and '80s, and penned little thereafter that did not invoke his ideas about influence.\n\n===Novel experiment===\nBloom's fascination with the fantasy novel ''[[A Voyage to Arcturus]]'' by [[David Lindsay (novelist)|David Lindsay]] led him to take a brief break from criticism in order to compose a sequel to Lindsay's novel. This novel, ''[[The Flight to Lucifer]]'', was Bloom's only work of fiction.<ref name=\"The Violet Apple\">{{cite web|url=http://www.violetapple.org.uk/notes/bloom_flighttolucifer.php|title=The Flight to Lucifer review|accessdate=September 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Religious criticism===\nBloom then entered a phase of what he called \"religious criticism\", beginning with ''Ruin the Sacred Truths: Poetry and Belief from the Bible to the Present'' (1989).\n\nIn ''The Book of J'' (1990), he and [[David Rosenberg (poet)|David Rosenberg]] (who translated the Biblical texts) portrayed one of the posited ancient documents that formed the basis of the first five books of the Bible (see [[documentary hypothesis]]) as the work of a great literary artist who had no intention of composing a [[dogmatic]]ally religious work (see [[Jahwist]]). They further envisaged this anonymous writer as a woman attached to the court of the successors of the Israelite kings [[David]] and [[King Solomon|Solomon]]\u2014a piece of speculation which drew much attention. Later, Bloom said that the speculations did not go far enough, and perhaps he should have identified J with the Biblical [[Bathsheba]].<ref>Bloom, Harold, ''The Western Canon. The Books and Schools of the Ages'', New York: Harcourt Brace & Company, 1994, p. 5.</ref> In ''Jesus and Yahweh: The Names Divine'' (2004), he revisits some of the territory he covered in ''The Book of J'' in discussing the significance of [[YHWH|Yahweh]] and [[Jesus of Nazareth]] as literary characters, while casting a critical eye on historical approaches and asserting the fundamental incompatibility of [[Christianity and Judaism]].\n\nIn ''[[The American Religion]]'' (1992), Bloom surveyed the major varieties of [[Protestant]] and post-Protestant religious faiths that originated in the United States and argued that, in terms of their psychological hold on their adherents, most shared more in common with [[gnosticism]] than with historical Christianity. The exception was the [[Jehovah's Witnesses]], whom Bloom regards as non-Gnostic. He elsewhere predicted that the [[Mormon]] and [[Pentecostal]] strains of [[American Christianity]] would overtake mainstream Protestant divisions in popularity in the next few decades. In ''Omens of Millennium'' (1996), Bloom identifies these American religious elements as on the periphery of an old \u2013 and not inherently Christian \u2013 gnostic, religious tradition which invokes a complex of ideas and experiences concerning [[angelology]], interpretation of dreams as [[prophecy]], [[near-death experience]]s, and [[millennialism]].<ref>Bloom (1996), p. 5.</ref>\n\nIn his essay in ''The Gospel of Thomas'', Bloom states that none of Thomas' [[Aramaic]] sayings have survived in the original language.<ref>Bloom, Harold. \"A Reading\", in ''The Gospel of Thomas: The Hidden Sayings of Jesus''. English translation and critical edition of the Coptic text by Marvin W. Meyer. San Francisco: HarperSanFrancisco, 1992, pp. 115 and 119.</ref> [[Marvin Meyer]] generally agreed and further confirmed that the earlier versions of that text were likely written in either Aramaic or Greek.<ref>Mayer, Marvin. \"Introduction\". The Gospel of Thomas. San Francisco: HarperSanFrancisco, 1992, p. 9.</ref> Meyer ends his introduction with an endorsement of much of Bloom's essay.<ref>Meyer (1992), p. 19.</ref> Bloom notes the other-worldliness of the Jesus in the Thomas sayings by making reference to \"the paradox also of the American Jesus.\"<ref>Meyer (1992), p. 119.</ref>\n\n===''The Western Canon''===\n''[[The Western Canon]]'' (1994), a survey of the major literary works of Europe and the Americas since the 14th century, focuses on 26 works he considered sublime and representative of their nations<ref>Bloom (1994), p. 2.</ref> and of the [[Western canon]].<ref>Bloom (1994), p. 11.</ref> Besides analyses of the canon's various representative works, Bloom's major concern in the volume was reclaiming literature from those he referred to as the \"[[School of Resentment]]\", the mostly academic critics who espoused a social purpose in reading. Bloom asserted that the goals of reading must be solitary [[aesthetic]] pleasure and self-insight rather than the goal of improving one's society held by \"forces of resentment\". He cast the latter as an absurd aim, writing: \"The idea that you benefit the insulted and injured by reading someone of their own origins rather than reading [[Shakespeare]] is one of the oddest illusions ever promoted by or in our schools.\" His position was that politics had no place in literary criticism, that a [[feminist]] or [[Marxist]] reading of ''[[Hamlet]]'' would tell us something about feminism and Marxism but probably nothing about ''Hamlet'' itself.\n\nIn addition to considering how much influence a writer had had on later writers, Bloom proposed the concept of \"canonical strangeness\" (cf. [[uncanny]]) as a benchmark of a literary work's merit. ''The Western Canon'' also included a list\u2014which aroused more widespread interest than anything else in the volume\u2014of all the Western works from antiquity to the present that Bloom considered either permanent members of the canon of literary classics, or (among more recent works) candidates for that status. Bloom said that he made the list off the top of his head at his editor's request, and that he did not stand by it.<ref name=vice />\n\n===Work on Shakespeare===\n[[File:Shakespeare.jpg|thumb|[[William Shakespeare]] (1564\u20131616)]]\n\nBloom had a deep appreciation for [[William Shakespeare]]<ref>Bloom (1994), pp.&nbsp;2\u20133.</ref> and considered him to be the supreme center of the Western canon.<ref>Bloom (1994), pp.&nbsp;24\u20135.</ref> The first edition of ''The Anxiety of Influence'' almost completely avoided Shakespeare, whom Bloom then considered barely touched by the psychological drama of anxiety. The second edition, published in 1997, added a long preface that mostly expounded Shakespeare's debt to [[Ovid]] and [[Geoffrey Chaucer|Chaucer]], and his [[agon#Literature|agon]] with contemporary [[Christopher Marlowe]], who set the stage for him by breaking free of ecclesiastical and moralizing overtones.\n\nIn his later survey, ''Shakespeare: The Invention of the Human'' (1998), Bloom provided an analysis of each of Shakespeare's 38 plays, \"twenty-four of which are masterpieces.\" Written as a companion to the general reader and theater-goer, Bloom declared that [[bardolatry]] \"ought to be even more a secular religion than it already is.\"<ref>Bloom, Harold. ''Shakespeare: The Invention of the Human''. New York: Riverhead, 1998, p. xix.</ref> He also contended in the work (as in the title) that Shakespeare \"invented\" humanity, in that he prescribed the now-common practice of \"overhearing\" ourselves, which drives our changes. The two paragons of his theory were [[Sir John Falstaff]] of ''[[Henry IV, Part 1|Henry IV]]'' and [[Prince Hamlet|Hamlet]], whom Bloom saw as representing self-satisfaction and self-loathing, respectively. Throughout ''Shakespeare'', characters from disparate plays were imagined alongside and interacting with each other. This has been decried by numerous contemporary academics and critics as harking back to the out of fashion character criticism of [[A. C. Bradley]] (and others), who gathered explicit praise in the book. As in ''The Western Canon'', Bloom criticized what he called the \"School of Resentment\" for its failure to live up to the challenge of Shakespeare's universality and for [[Balkanization|balkanizing]] the study of literature through multicultural and [[New Historicism|historicist]] departments. Asserting Shakespeare's singular popularity throughout the world, Bloom proclaimed him the only truly multicultural author. Repudiating the \"social energies\" to which historicists ascribed Shakespeare's authorship, Bloom pronounced his modern academic foes \u2013 and indeed, all of society \u2013 to be but \"a parody of Shakespearian energies.\"\n\n===2000s and 2010s===\nBloom consolidated his work on the western canon with the publication of ''How to Read and Why'' (2000) and ''Genius: A Mosaic of One Hundred Exemplary Creative Minds'' (2003). ''Hamlet: Poem Unlimited'' (also 2003) is an amendment to ''Shakespeare: Invention of the Human'' written after he decided the chapter on ''Hamlet'' in that earlier book had been too focused on the textual question of the ''[[Ur-Hamlet]]'' to cover his most central thoughts on the play itself. Some elements of religious criticism were combined with his secular criticism in ''Where Shall Wisdom Be Found'' (2004), and a more complete return to religious criticism was marked by the publication of ''Jesus and Yahweh: The Names Divine'' (2005). Throughout the decade he also compiled, edited and introduced several major anthologies of poetry.\n\nBloom took part in the documentary, the ''[[Apparition of the Eternal Church]]'' (2006), made by [[Paul Festa]]. This documentary centered on many individuals' reactions to hearing, for the first time, Olivier Messiaen's organ piece ''[[Apparition de l'\u00e9glise \u00e9ternelle]]''.\n\nBloom began a book under the working title of ''Living Labyrinth'', centering on Shakespeare and [[Walt Whitman]], which was published as ''The Anatomy of Influence: Literature as a Way of Life'' (2011).\n\nIn July 2011, after the publication of ''The Anatomy of Influence'' and after finishing work on ''The Shadow of a Great Rock'', Bloom was working on three further projects:\n* ''Achievement in the Evening Land from Emerson to [[Faulkner]]'', a history of American literature following the canonical model, which ultimately developed into his book ''The Daemon Knows: Literary Greatness and the American Sublime'' (2015).\n* ''The Hum of Thoughts Evaded in the Mind: A Literary Memoir'', which ultimately developed into his book ''Possessed by Memory: The Inward Light of Criticism'' (2019).\n* a play with the working title ''Walt Whitman: A Musical Pageant''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radioopensource.org/harold-bloom-on-the-playing-field-of-poetry/|title=Harold Bloom: On the Playing Field of Poetry - Open Source with Christopher Lydon|author=|date=July 5, 2011|website=www.radioopensource.org|accessdate=March 27, 2018}}</ref> By November 2011, Bloom had changed the title of the play to ''To You Whoever You Are: A Pageant Celebrating Walt Whitman''.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/13/opinion/sunday/will-this-election-be-the-mormon-breakthrough.html \"Will This Election Be the Mormon Breakthrough?\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', November 12, 2011.</ref>\n\n==Influence==\n[[File:Samuel Johnson by Joshua Reynolds.jpg|thumb|In ''[[The Western Canon: The Books and School of the Ages|The Western Canon]]'', Bloom claimed that [[Samuel Johnson]] was \"unmatched by any critic in any nation before or after him.\"]]\n\nIn 1986, Bloom credited [[Northrop Frye]] as his nearest precursor. He told [[Imre Salusinszky]] in 1986: \"In terms of my own theorizations&nbsp;... the precursor proper has to be Northrop Frye. I purchased and read ''[[Fearful Symmetry (Frye)|Fearful Symmetry]]'' a week or two after it had come out and reached the bookstore in Ithaca, New York. It ravished my heart away. I have tried to find an alternative father in Mr. [[Kenneth Burke]], who is a charming fellow and a very powerful critic, but I don't come from Burke, I come out of Frye.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prelectur.stanford.edu/lecturers/bloom/interviews.html#roots|title=Presidential Lectures: Harold Bloom: Interviews|author=|date=|website=prelectur.stanford.edu|accessdate=March 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHowever, in ''Anatomy of Influence'' (2011), he wrote \"I no longer have the patience to read anything by Frye\" and nominated Angus Fletcher of the City University of New York among his living contemporaries as his \"critical guide and conscience\" and elsewhere that year recommended Fletcher's ''Colors of the Mind'' and ''The Mirror and the Lamp'' by [[M. H. Abrams]]. In this late phase of his career, Bloom also emphasized the tradition of earlier critics such as [[William Hazlitt]], Ralph Waldo Emerson, [[Walter Pater]], [[A. C. Bradley]], and [[Samuel Johnson]], describing Johnson in ''The Western Canon'' as \"unmatched by any critic in any nation before or after him\". In his 2012 Foreword to the book ''The Fourth Dimension of a Poem'' (WW Norton, 2012), Bloom indicated the influence which M. H. Abrams had upon him in his years at Cornell University.<ref>M. H. Abrams. ''The Fourth Dimension of a Poem'' (WW Norton, 2012).</ref>\n\nBloom's theory of poetic influence regards the development of [[Western literature]] as a process of borrowing and misreading. Writers find their creative inspiration in previous writers and begin by imitating those writers in order to develop a poetic voice of their own; however, they must make their own work different from that of their precursors. As a result, Bloom argues, authors of real power must inevitably \"misread\" their precursors' works in order to make room for fresh imaginings.<ref>{{cite journal| url=http://www.theparisreview.org/interviews/2225/the-art-of-criticism-no-1-harold-bloom| title=Harold Bloom, The Art of Criticism No. 1| journal=Paris Review| volume=Spring 1991| issue=118| date=Spring 1991| author=Antonio Weiss}}</ref><ref>Paul Fry, [http://oyc.yale.edu/english/engl-300/lecture-14 \"Engl 300: Introduction To Theory Of Literature\"]. Lecture 14 \u2013 Influence. Open Yale lectures on the influence of Bloom and Eliot.</ref>\n\nObservers often identified Bloom with [[deconstruction]] in the past, but he himself never admitted to sharing more than a few ideas with the deconstructionists. He told [[Robert Moynihan]] in 1983, \"What I think I have in common with the school of deconstruction is the mode of negative thinking or negative awareness, in the technical, philosophical sense of the negative, but which comes to me through [[apophatic theology|negative theology]]&nbsp;... There is no escape, there is simply the given, and there is nothing that we can do.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview with Harold Bloom|url=https://prelectur.stanford.edu/lecturers/bloom/interviews.html|work=Stanford Presidential Lectures in the Humanities and Arts|publisher=Stanford University|accessdate=March 15, 2014}} Excerpted from \"Interview: Harold Bloom interviewed by Robert Moynihan\" ''Diacritics : A Review of Contemporary Criticism'' vol. 13 , No. 3 (Fall, 1983), pp. 57\u201368.</ref>\n\nBloom's association with the [[Western canon]] provoked a substantial interest in his opinion concerning the relative importance of contemporary writers. In the late 1980s, Bloom told an interviewer: \"Probably the most powerful living Western writer is [[Samuel Beckett]]. He's certainly the most authentic.\"<ref>[http://new.bostonreview.net/BR11.1/bloom.html \"Candidates for Survival: A talk with Harold Bloom\"], ''Boston Review'', February, 1989; {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140315224424/http://new.bostonreview.net/BR11.1/bloom.html |date=March 15, 2014 }}</ref> After Beckett died in 1989, Bloom pointed towards other authors as the new main figures of the Western literary canon.\n\nConcerning British writers: \"[[Geoffrey Hill]] is the strongest British poet now active\", and \"no other contemporary British novelist seems to me to be of [[Iris Murdoch]]'s eminence\". After Murdoch died, Bloom expressed admiration for novelists such as [[Peter Ackroyd]], [[Will Self]], [[John Banville]], and [[A. S. Byatt]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Bloom|first=Harold|title=Genius : a mosaic of one hundred exemplary creative minds|year=2002|publisher=Warner Books|location=New York|isbn=0-446-69129-1|page=648|quote=There are a few affinities, except perhaps with the admirable Antonia Byatt, in the generation after: novelists I also now admire, like Will Self, Peter Ackroyd, and John Banville.}}</ref>\n\nIn ''Genius: A Mosaic of One Hundred Exemplary Creative Minds'' (2003), he named the [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]] writer and Nobel Prize winner [[Jos\u00e9 Saramago]] as \"the most gifted novelist alive in the world today\", and as \"one of the last titans of an expiring literary genre\".\n\nOf American novelists, he declared in 2003 that \"there are four living American novelists I know of who are still at work and who deserve our praise\".<ref>[http://www.boston.com/news/globe/editorial_opinion/oped/articles/2003/09/24/dumbing_down_american_readers/ \"Dumbing Down American Readers\"], ''Boston Globe'', September 24, 2003. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060617015302/http://www.boston.com/news/globe/editorial_opinion/oped/articles/2003/09/24/dumbing_down_american_readers/ |date=June 17, 2006 }}</ref> He claimed that \"they write the Style of our Age, each has composed canonical works,\" and he identified them as [[Thomas Pynchon]], [[Philip Roth]], [[Cormac McCarthy]], and [[Don DeLillo]]. He named their strongest works as, respectively, ''[[Gravity's Rainbow]]'', ''[[The Crying of Lot 49]]'' and ''[[Mason & Dixon]]''; ''[[American Pastoral]]'' and ''[[Sabbath's Theater]]''; ''[[Blood Meridian]]''; and ''[[Underworld (DeLillo novel)|Underworld]]''. He added to this estimate the work of [[John Crowley (author)|John Crowley]], with special interest in his [[Aegypt Sequence]] and novel ''[[Little, Big]]'' saying that \"only a handful of living writers in English can equal him as a stylist, and most of them are poets&nbsp;... only Philip Roth consistently writes on Crowley's level\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Bloom|first=Harold|title=Snake's-hands : the fiction of John Crowley|year=2003|publisher=Cosmos Books|location=[Canton, OH]|isbn=1-58715-509-5|page=10|url=https://books.google.com/?id=JsaIP2n6xvgC&printsec=frontcover&dq=old+snake-hands#v=onepage&q=Crowley%20Roth&f=false|chapter=Preface}}</ref>\n\nIn ''Kabbalah and Criticism'' (1975), Bloom identified [[Robert Penn Warren]], [[James Merrill]], [[John Ashbery]], and [[Elizabeth Bishop]] as the most important living American poets. By the 1990s, he regularly named [[A. R. Ammons]] along with Ashbery and Merrill, and he later identified [[Henri Cole]] as the crucial American poet of the generation following those three. He expressed great admiration for the Canadian poets [[Anne Carson]], particularly her [[verse novel]] ''Autobiography of Red,'' and [[A. F. Moritz]], whom Bloom called \"a true poet.\"<ref>{{Citation | last=Hollander|first=John|authorlink=John Hollander|contribution=Enriching Shadow: A.F. Moritz's Early Poems|editor-last=Moritz|editor-first=A.F.|title=Early Poems|pages=17|publisher=Insomniac Press|place=Toronto|year=2002|url=https://books.google.com/?id=owHzhPCAEv8C&pg=PA17&lpg=PA17&dq=bloom+%22true+poet%22#v=onepage&q=moritz%20bloom%20%22true%20poet%22&f=false|isbn=9781897414774}}</ref> Bloom also listed [[Jay Wright (poet)|Jay Wright]] as one of only a handful of major living poets.<ref>Harold Bloom (ed.), ''Modern Critical Interpretations: Jay Wright'', New York: Chelsea House, 2003.</ref>\n\nBloom's introduction to ''Modern Critical Interpretations: Thomas Pynchon's Gravity's Rainbow'' (1986) features his canon of the \"twentieth-century American Sublime\", the greatest works of American art produced in the 20th century. Playwright [[Tony Kushner]] sees Bloom as an important influence on his work.<ref>Harold Bloom (ed.), ''Modern Critical Interpretations: Thomas Pynchon's Gravity's Rainbow'', New York: Chelsea House, 1986.</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nFor many years, Bloom's writings have drawn polarized responses, even among established literary scholars. Bloom was called \"probably the most celebrated literary critic in the United States\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2002/oct/12/featuresreviews.guardianreview14 | location=London | work=[[The Guardian]] | first=Frank | last=Kermode| authorlink = Frank Kermode | title=Review: Genius by Harold Bloom | date=October 12, 2002}}</ref> and \"America's best-known man of letters\".<ref name=\"powells1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.powells.com/review/2006_05_11.html?&PID=18|title=Powell's Books - The World's Largest Independent Bookstore|first=Used, New, and Out of Print Books - We Buy and Sell - Powell's|last=Books|date=|website=www.powells.com|accessdate=March 27, 2018}}</ref> A ''[[New York Times]]'' article in 1994 said that many younger critics understand Bloom as an \"outdated oddity,\"<ref name=\"nytbegley\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/11/01/specials/bloom-colossus.html | location=New York | work=[[The New York Times]] | first=Adam | last=Begley| authorlink = Adam Begley| title=Review: Colossus Among Critics: Harold Bloom | date=September 24, 1994}}</ref> whereas a 1998 ''New York Times'' article called him \"one of the most gifted of contemporary critics.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/11/01/reviews/981101.01shapirt.html | location=New York | work=[[The New York Times]] | first=James | last=Shapiro| title=Soul of the Age | date=November 1, 1998}}</ref>\n\n[[James Wood (critic)|James Wood]] described Bloom as \"Vatic, repetitious, imprecisely reverential, though never without a peculiar charm of his own\u2014a kind of campiness, in fact\u2014Bloom as a literary critic in the last few years has been largely unimportant.\"<ref name=\"powells1\"/> Bloom responded to questions about Wood in an interview by saying: \"There are period pieces in criticism as there are period pieces in the novel and in poetry. The wind blows and they will go away&nbsp;... There's nothing to the man&nbsp;... I don't want to talk about him\".<ref name=\"vice\">{{cite web|last=Pearson |first=Jesse | authorlink =Jesse Pearson (writer)|url=https://www.vice.com/read/harold-bloom-431-v15n12 |title=Harold Bloom |work=[[VICE United States]] |date=December 2, 2008 |accessdate=June 25, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014172844/http://www.vice.com/read/harold-bloom-431-v15n12 |archive-date=October 14, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 21st century, Bloom often found himself at the center of literary controversy after criticizing popular writers such as [[Adrienne Rich]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://new.bostonreview.net/BR23.3/perloff.html |title=Visionary Company|website=Boston Review|access-date=September 23, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925070808/http://new.bostonreview.net/BR23.3/perloff.html |archive-date=September 25, 2015 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> [[Maya Angelou]],<ref>\"Miss [[Maya Angelou]] cannot write her way out of a paper bag!\"\nKenton Robinson, \"Foe To Those Who Would Shape Literature To Their Own End Dissent in Bloom\" ''[[Hartford Courant]]'' October 4, 1994 E.1</ref> and [[David Foster Wallace]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Koski|first=Lorna|title=The Full Harold Bloom|url=http://www.wwd.com/eye/people/the-full-bloom-3592315?full=true|accessdate=October 19, 2012|newspaper=[[Women's Wear Daily]]|date=April 26, 2011}}</ref> In the pages of ''[[The Paris Review]]'', he criticized the [[populism|populist]]-leaning [[poetry slam]], saying: \"It is the death of art.\" When [[Doris Lessing]] was awarded the [[Nobel Prize in Literature]], he bemoaned the \"pure political correctness\" of the award to an author of \"fourth-rate science fiction,\" although he conceded his appreciation of Lessing's earlier work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.today.com/id/12784353|agency=Associated Press|title=U.K.'s Lessing wins Nobel Prize in literature|author=|date=October 11, 2007|website=msn.com|accessdate=March 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMormonVoices, a group associated with [[FairMormon|Foundation for Apologetic Information & Research]], included Bloom on its Top Ten Anti-Mormon Statements of 2011 list for stating \"The current head of the Mormon Church, [[Thomas S. Monson]], known to his followers as 'prophet, seer and revelator,' is indistinguishable from the secular plutocratic oligarchs who exercise power in our supposed democracy\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/print/700213557/Group-lists-Top-Ten-Anti-Mormon-Statements-of-2011.html |title=Group lists Top Ten Anti-Mormon Statements of 2011 |date=January 8, 2012 |work=[[Deseret News]] |first=Joseph |last=Walker}}</ref>\n\n==Selected bibliography==\n\n===Books===\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* ''Shelley's Mythmaking.'' New Haven: Yale University Press, 1959.\n* ''The Visionary Company: A Reading of English Romantic Poetry.'' Garden City, N.Y.: Doubleday, 1961. Revised and enlarged edn. Ithaca: Cornell University Press, 1971.\n* ''Blake's Apocalypse: A Study in Poetic Argument.'' Anchor Books: New York: Doubleday and Co., 1963.\n* ''The Literary Criticism of John Ruskin.''; edited with introduction. New York: DoubleDay, 1965.\n* ''Walter Pater: Marius the Epicurean''; edition with introduction. New York: New American Library, 1970.\n* ''Romanticism and Consciousness: Essays in Criticism.''; edited with introduction. New York: Norton, 1970.\n* ''Yeats.'' New York: Oxford University Press, 1970. {{ISBN|0-19-501603-3}}\n* ''The Ringers in the Tower: Studies in Romantic Tradition.'' Chicago: University of Chicago Press, 1971.\n* ''[[The Anxiety of Influence|The Anxiety of Influence: A Theory of Poetry]]''. New York: Oxford University Press, 1973; 2nd edn, 1997. {{ISBN|0-19-511221-0}}\n* ''The Selected Writings of Walter Pater''; edition with introduction and notes. New York: New American Library, 1974.\n* ''A Map of Misreading.'' New York: Oxford University Press, 1975.\n* ''Kabbalah and Criticism.'' New York : Seabury Press, 1975. {{ISBN|0-8264-0242-9}}\n* ''Poetry and Repression: Revisionism from Blake to Stevens.'' New Haven: Yale University Press, 1976.\n* ''Figures of Capable Imagination.'' New York: Seabury Press, 1976.\n* ''Wallace Stevens: The Poems of our Climate.'' Ithaca, N.Y.: Cornell University Press, 1977.\n* ''Deconstruction and Criticism.'' New York: Seabury Press, 1980.\n* ''[[The Flight to Lucifer|The Flight to Lucifer: A Gnostic Fantasy]].'' New York: Vintage Books, 1980. {{ISBN|0-394-74323-7}}\n* ''Agon: Towards a Theory of Revisionism.'' New York : Oxford University Press, 1982.\n* ''The Breaking of the Vessels.'' Chicago: University of Chicago Press, 1982.\n* ''The Poetics of Influence: New and Selected Criticism.'' New Haven: Henry R. Schwab, 1988.\n* ''Ruin the Sacred Truths: Poetry and Belief from the Bible to the Present.'' Cambridge, Mass.: Harvard University Press, 1989.\n* ''The Book of J: Translated from the Hebrew by David Rosenberg; Interpreted by Harold Bloom.'' New York: Grove Press, 1990 {{ISBN|0-8021-4191-9}}\n* ''The Gospel of Thomas: The Hidden Sayings of Jesus''; translation with introduction, critical edition of the Coptic text and notes by Marvin Meyer, with an interpretation by Harold Bloom. San Francisco: HarperSanFrancisco, 1992.\n* ''[[The American Religion: The Emergence of the Post-Christian Nation]]''; Touchstone Books; {{ISBN|0-671-86737-7}} (1992; August 1993)\n* ''[[The Western Canon (book)|The Western Canon: The Books and School of the Ages]]''. New York: Harcourt Brace, 1994.\n* ''Omens of Millennium: The Gnosis of Angels, Dreams, and Resurrection.'' New York: Riverhead Books, 1996.\n* ''[[Shakespeare: The Invention of the Human]].'' New York: 1998. {{ISBN|1-57322-751-X}}\n* ''How to Read and Why.'' New York: 2000. {{ISBN|0-684-85906-8}}\n* ''Stories and Poems for Extremely Intelligent Children of All Ages.'' New York: 2001.\n* ''El futur de la imaginaci\u00f3 (The Future of the Imagination).'' Barcelona: [[Anagrama]] / Emp\u00faries, 2002. {{ISBN|84-7596-927-5}}\n* ''[[Genius: A Mosaic of One Hundred Exemplary Creative Minds]].'' New York: 2003. {{ISBN|0-446-52717-3}}\n* ''Hamlet: Poem Unlimited''. New York: 2003.\n* ''The Best Poems of the English Language: From Chaucer Through Frost.'' New York: 2004. {{ISBN|0-06-054041-9}}\n* ''Where Shall Wisdom Be Found?'' New York: 2004. {{ISBN|1-57322-284-4}}\n* ''[[Jesus and Yahweh: The Names Divine]]''. 2005. {{ISBN|1-57322-322-0}}\n* ''American Religious Poems: An Anthology By Harold Bloom''. 2006. {{ISBN|1-931082-74-X}}\n* ''Fallen Angels'', illustrated by Mark Podwal. Yale University Press, 2007. {{ISBN|0-300-12348-5}}\n* ''Till I End My Song: A Gathering of Last Poems'' Harper, 2010. {{ISBN|0-06-192305-2}}\n* ''[[The Anatomy of Influence: Literature as a Way of Life]]''. Yale University Press, 2011. {{ISBN|0-300-16760-1}}\n* ''The Shadow of a Great Rock: A Literary Appreciation of The King James Bible''. Yale University Press, 2011. {{ISBN|0-300-16683-4}}\n* ''The Daemon Knows: Literary Greatness and the American Sublime''. Spiegel & Grau, 2015. {{ISBN|0-812-99782-4}}\n* ''Falstaff: Give Me Life''. Scribner, 2017. {{ISBN|978-1-5011-6413-2}}\n* ''Cleopatra: I Am Fire and Air''. Scribner, 2017. {{ISBN|978-1-5011-6416-3}}\n* ''Lear: The Great Image of Authority''. Scribner, 2018. {{ISBN|978-1-5011-6419-4}}\n* ''Iago: The Strategies of Evil''. Scribner, 2018. {{ISBN|978-1-5011-6422-4}}\n* ''Macbeth: A Dagger of the Mind''. Scribner, 2019. {{ISBN|978-1-5011-6425-5}}\n* ''Possessed by Memory: The Inward Light of Criticism''. Knopf, 2019. {{ISBN|978-0-5255-2088-7}}\n{{refend}}\n\n===Articles===\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/12/21/home/stevens-vendler.html \"On Extended Wings\"]; Wallace Stevens' Longer Poems. By Helen Hennessy Vendler, (Review), ''[[The New York Times]]'', October 5, 1969.\n* \"Poets' meeting in the heyday of their youth; A Single Summer With Lord Byron\", ''The New York Times'', February 15, 1970.\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/1970/11/22/archives/an-angels-spirit-in-a-decaying-and-active-body.html \"An angel's spirit in a decaying (and active) body\"], ''The New York Times'', November 22, 1970.\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/1975/11/12/archives/the-use-of-poetry.html \"The Use of Poetry\"], ''The New York Times'', November 12, 1975.\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/1976/04/18/archives/northrop-frye-exalting-the-designs-of-romance-the-secular-scripture.html \"Northrop Frye exalting the designs of romance; The Secular Scripture\"], ''The New York Times'', April 18, 1976.\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/1977/08/04/archives/on-solitude-in-america.html \"On Solitude in America\"], ''The New York Times'', August 4, 1977.\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/1978/02/05/archives/the-criticpoet.html \"The Critic/Poet\"], ''The New York Times'', February 5, 1978.\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/1979/07/22/archives/a-fusion-of-traditions-rosenberg.html \"A Fusion of Traditions: The Collected Works of Isaac Rosenberg\"], ''The New York Times'', July 22, 1979.\n* \"Straight Forth Out of Self\", ''The New York Times'', June 22, 1980.\n* \"The Heavy Burden of the Past; Poets\", ''The New York Times'', January 4, 1981.\n* \"The Pictures of the Poet; The Painting and Drawings of William Blake, by [[Martin Butlin]]. Vol. I, Text. Vol. II, Plates\" (review), ''The New York Times'', January 3, 1982.\n* \"A Novelist's Bible; The Story of the Stories, The Chosen People and Its God. By Dan Jacobson\" (review), ''The New York Times'', October 17, 1982.\n* \"Isaac Bashevis Singer's Jeremiad; The Penitent, By Isaac Bashevis Singer\" (review), ''The New York Times'', September 25, 1983.\n* \"Domestic Derangements; A Late Divorce, By A. B. Yehoshua Translated by Hillel Halkin\" (review), ''The New York Times'', February 19, 1984.\n* \"War Within the Walls; In the Freud Archives, By Janet Malcolm\" (review), ''The New York Times'', May 27, 1984.\n* \"His Long Ordeal by Laughter; Zuckerman Bound, A Trilogy and Epilogue. By Philip Roth\" (review), ''The New York Times'', May 19, 1985.\n* \"A Comedy of Worldly Salvation; The Good Apprentice, By Iris Murdoch\" (review), ''The New York Times'', January 12, 1986.\n* \"Freud, the Greatest Modern Writer\" (review), ''The New York Times'', March 23, 1986.\n* \"Passionate Beholder of America in Trouble; Look Homeward, A Life of Thomas Wolfe. By David Herbert Donald\" (review), ''The New York Times'', February 8, 1987.\n* \"The Book of the Father; The Messiah of Stockholm, By Cynthia Ozick\" (review), ''The New York Times'', March 22, 1987.\n* \"[https://www.nytimes.com/1988/01/31/books/still-haunted-by-covenant.html?pagewanted=all Still Haunted by Covenant\"] (review), ''The New York Times'', January 31, 1988.\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/1992/04/26/opinion/new-heyday-of-gnostic-heresies.html?pagewanted=all \"New Heyday of Gnostic Heresies\"], ''The New York Times'', April 26, 1992.\n* \"A Jew Among the Cossacks; The first English translation of Isaac Babel's journal about his service with the Russian cavalry. 1920 Diary, By Isaac Babel\" (review), ''The New York Times'', June 4, 1995.\n* \"Kaddish; By Leon Wieseltier\" (review), ''The New York Times'', October 4, 1998.\n* \"View; On First Looking into Gates's Crichton\", ''The New York Times'', June 4, 2000.\n* \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2000/12/06/opinion/what-ho-malvolio.html What Ho, Malvolio!]'; The election, as Shakespeare might have seen it\", ''The New York Times'', December 6, 2000.\n* \"Macbush\" (play), ''Vanity Fair'', April 2004.\n* [http://www.nybooks.com/articles/20338 \"The Lost Jewish Culture\"], ''[[The New York Review of Books]]'' 54/11 (June 28, 2007) : 44\u201347 [reviews ''The Dreams of the Poem: Hebrew Poetry from Muslim and Christian Spain, 950\u20131492'', translated, edited, and with an introduction by [[Peter Cole]]\n* [http://www.nybooks.com/articles/22020 \"The Glories of Yiddish\"] ''[[The New York Review of Books]]'' 55/17 (November 6, 2008) [reviews ''History of the Yiddish Language'', by [[Max Weinreich]], edited by [[Paul Glasser]], translated from the Yiddish by [[Shlomo Noble]] with the assistance of [[Joshua A. Fishman]]]\n* \"[http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2009/dec/03/yahweh-meets-r-crumb/ Yahweh Meets R. Crumb]\", ''[[The New York Review of Books]]'', 56/19 (December 3, 2009) [reviews ''The Book of Genesis'', illustrated by [[Robert Crumb|R. Crumb]]]\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/13/opinion/sunday/will-this-election-be-the-mormon-breakthrough.html \"Will This Election Be the Mormon Breakthrough?\"], ''The New York Times'', November 12, 2011.\n* [http://www.newsweek.com/richard-iii-victim-or-monster-asks-harold-bloom-63257 \"Richard III: Victim or Monster? Asks Harold Bloom\"], ''[[Newsweek]]'', February 11, 2013.\n* [http://tabletmag.com/jewish-arts-and-culture/books/159759/harold-bloom-peter-cole Introduction to ''The Invention of Influence'' by Peter Cole], ''Talbet'', January 21, 2014.\n{{refend}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n* [[Covering cherub]]\n* [[List of thinkers influenced by deconstruction]]\n* [[School of resentment]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite book|author =Allen, Graham| title=Harold Bloom: Poetics of Conflict|publisher= Harvester Wheatsheaf |location=New York, NY|date= 1994}}\n* {{cite book|last=Basbanes|first= Nicholas A. |title=Every Book Its Reader: The Power of the Printed Word to Stir the World|url=https://archive.org/details/everybookitsread00basb |url-access=registration |publisher= HarperCollins|location= New York|date= 2005|pages= [https://archive.org/details/everybookitsread00basb/page/224 224\u2013238]|author-link= Nicholas A. Basbanes}}\n* {{cite book|author=Bielik-Robson, Agata|url=http://www.nupress.northwestern.edu/Title/tabid/68/ISBN/0-8101-2728-8/Default.aspx|title=The Saving Lie: Harold Bloom and Deconstruction|publisher=Northwestern|date=2011|isbn=978-0-8101-2728-9}}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* {{cite news| author=Bloom, Harold| url=http://books.guardian.co.uk/review/story/0,12084,962070,00.html |title=The sage of Concord|date= May 24, 2003|work=The Guardian}} \n*{{cite news|author=Bloom, Harold|work=[[Guardian Unlimited]] |title=Article on Ralph Waldo Emerson }}\n* {{cite web|author=Bloom, Harold| url=http://prelectur.stanford.edu/lecturers/bloom/interviews.html |title=Excerpts from various Bloom interviews|website= The Stanford Presidential Lecture Series}}\n* {{cite news|author=Bloom, Harold | url=http://www.boston.com/news/globe/editorial_opinion/oped/articles/2003/09/24/dumbing_down_american_readers/ |title=Dumbing down American readers|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|date= September 24, 2003}}\n* {{cite news| title=Can 35 Million Book Buyers Be Wrong? Yes| author=Bloom, Harold |work= The Wall Street Journal|date= July 11, 2000}} His famous criticism of the [[Harry Potter]] series.\n* {{cite news| url= https://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/12/opinion/12bloom.html |title=Out of Panic, Self-Reliance|work=The New York Times|author=Bloom, Harold|date= October 12, 2008}}\n* {{cite web|author=Bloom, Harold|work=The New York Times| url=http://www.nybooks.com/authors/1343 |title=List of Bloom's contributions to ''The New York Review of Books''}}\n* {{cite book |title=Contemporary Literary Criticism |series=Contemporary Literary Criticism Series |chapter=Harold Bloom 1930\u2013 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/contemporarylite24detr/page/70 70]\u201383 |volume=24 |publisher=Gale |location=Detroit |year=1983 |isbn=9780810301115 |url=https://archive.org/details/contemporarylite24detr |url-access=registration }}\n* Burrow, Colin, \"The Magic Bloomschtick\" (review of Harold Bloom, ''The American Canon: Literary Genius from Emerson to Pynchon'', edited by [[David Mikics]], Library of America, October 2019, 426 pp., {{ISBN|978 1 59853 640 9}}), ''[[London Review of Books]]'', vol. 41, no. 22 (21 November 2019), pp. 21\u201325. \"Harold Bloom will be remembered as a great provoker \u2013 of thought, of laughter, and of resistance. He didn't permanently reconfigure the literary landscape, but the idiosyncratic path he tracked across it is one few could follow.\" (Final two sentences of Burrow's review, p. 25.)  \n* {{cite book|author=De Bolla, Peter| title=Harold Bloom: Toward Historical Rhetorics|publisher=Routledge|location=New York, NY|date= 1988}}\n* {{cite journal|journal=Dictionary of Literary Biography|volume= 67|title= Modern American Critics since 1955|publisher= Gale|date= 1988}}\n* {{cite book|author=Fite, David|title=Harold Bloom: The Rhetoric of Romantic Vision|url=https://archive.org/details/haroldbloomrheto0000fite|url-access=registration|publisher= University of Massachusetts Press |location=Amherst|date= 1985}}\n*{{cite book|author= Moynihan, Robert|title=A Recent Imagining: Interviews with Harold Bloom, Geoffrey Hartman, J. Hillis Miller, Paul De Man|publisher= Archon|date= 1986}}\n*{{cite book|author= Saurberg, Lars Ole|title=Versions of the Past\u2014Visions of the Future: The Canonical in the Criticism of T.S. Eliot, F.R. Leavis, Northrop Frye, and Harold Bloom |publisher= St. Martin's Press |location=New York, NY|date= 1997}}\n* {{cite book| author=Scherr, Barry J.|title=D. H. Lawrence's Response to Plato: A Bloomian Interpretation |publisher=P. Lang |location=New York, NY|date= 1995}}\n* {{cite book\n  |title = The Salt Companion to Harold Bloom\n  |editor1-last = Sellars\n  |editor1-first = Roy\n  |editor2-last = Allen\n  |editor2-first = Graham\n  |publisher = [[Salt Publishing]]\n  |year = 2007\n  |isbn = 9781876857202\n}}\n* {{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5048309 |title=Interview with Bloom on NPR, regarding his book ''Jesus and Yahweh: The Names Divine''|work=[[All Things Considered]]|publisher=NPR}}\n* {{cite news|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/conversation/july-dec00/bloom_8-29.html |title=Interview with Bloom regarding his book ''How to Read and Why'' |date=2000|work=[[The NewsHour]] with [[Jim Lehrer]] }}\n* {{cite news|url=http://www.claremont.org/writings/crb/spring2006/balint.html|title=God and Harold at Yale|date=April 2014|work=Claremont Review|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061008103336/http://www.claremont.org/writings/crb/spring2006/balint.html|archivedate=October 8, 2006}}\n* {{cite news|work=Eurozine|url=http://www.eurozine.com/articles/2005-10-07-bloom-en.html|title=Interview regarding ''Breakfast with Brontosaurus''|date=October 26, 2004|author=Lesinska, Ieva|access-date=October 29, 2005|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051101222832/http://www.eurozine.com/articles/2005-10-07-bloom-en.html|archive-date=November 1, 2005|url-status=dead}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/lydon/2003/09/03 |title=Radio interview |author=Lydon, Christopher |website=Harvard Law Weblogs|date= September 3, 2003}}\n* {{cite news|author=Rothenberg, Jennie| url=https://www.theatlantic.com/unbound/interviews/int2003-07-16.htm |title=Interview with Jennie Rothenberg|work=The Atlantic|date= July 16, 2003}}\n* {{cite news|author=Wood, James| url=https://newrepublic.com/article/65417/the-misreader |title=The Misreader|work=The New Republic|date= May 1, 2006}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://english.yale.edu/people/tenured-and-tenure-track-faculty-professors/harold-bloom}} at [[Yale University]]\n* {{Charlie Rose|1576}}\n* {{C-SPAN|haroldbloom}}\n** {{cite web |url= http://www.c-spanvideo.org/program/176255-1 |title= In Depth with Harold Bloom |work= Interview |date= May 4, 2003 |first= Joseph I. |last= Epstein |publisher= C-SPAN }}\n* {{Worldcat id|lccn-n79-3258}}\n* {{NYTtopic|people/b/harold_bloom}}\n* [http://prelectur.stanford.edu/lecturers/bloom/ Harold Bloom] at [[Stanford University Centers and Institutes|Stanford Presidential Lectures]]\n* {{cite web |url= http://www.booknotes.org/Watch/157968-1/Harold+Bloom.aspx |publisher= [[Booknotes]] |title= How to Read and Why |date= September 3, 2000 |work= Interview |first= Brian |last= Lamb |access-date= December 27, 2011 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20121004142802/http://www.booknotes.org/Watch/157968-1/Harold+Bloom.aspx |archive-date= October 4, 2012 |url-status= dead |df= mdy-all }}\n* {{cite web |url= http://www.sobriquetmagazine.com/books/2015/08/anarchic-transports-a-review-of-harold-blooms-the-daemon-knows-literary-greatness-and-the-american-s.html |title= Anarchic Transports: A Review of Harold Bloom's ''The Daemon Knows: Literary Greatness and the American Sublime'' |first= Robert Savino |last= Oventile |date= August 8, 2015 |publisher= Sobriquet Magazine |work= Review }}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bloom, Harold}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Pembroke College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:American academics of English literature]]\n[[Category:American literary critics]]\n[[Category:American people of Belarusian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Ukrainian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:The Bronx High School of Science alumni]]\n[[Category:Cornell University alumni]]\n[[Category:Critics of postmodernism]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:Jewish American academics]]\n[[Category:Jewish scholars]]\n[[Category:Literary critics of English]]\n[[Category:MacArthur Fellows]]\n[[Category:Members of the American Academy of Arts and Letters]]\n[[Category:New York University faculty]]\n[[Category:People from the Bronx]]\n[[Category:Shakespearean scholars]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:Yale University faculty]]\n[[Category:Yale Sterling Professors]]\n[[Category:William Blake scholars]]\n[[Category:20th-century American educators]]\n[[Category:21st-century American educators]]\n[[Category:20th-century American writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American writers]]\n[[Category:W. B. Yeats scholars]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the screenwriter|Harold Jack Bloom}}\n{{Hatnote|Harold Bloom should not be confused with American philosopher [[Allan Bloom]].}}\n{{short description|American literary critic, scholar, and writer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Harold Bloom\n| image = Harold Bloom (Agon portrait).jpg\n| caption = Photo portrait from the [[dust jacket]] of ''Agon: Towards a Theory of Revisionism'' (1982)\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1930|7|11}}\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2019|10|14|1930|07|11}}\n| death_place = [[New Haven, Connecticut]], U.S.\n| birth_place = [[New York City]], New York, U.S.\n| occupation = [[literary criticism|Literary critic]], writer, professor\n| education = [[Cornell University]] (B.A.)<br/>[[Yale University]] (Ph.D.)<br/>[[Pembroke College, Cambridge]]\n| genre = \n| movement = [[Aestheticism]], [[Romanticism]]\n| notableworks = \n| spouse = {{marriage|Jeanne Gould|1958}}\n| children = 2\n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Harold Bloom''' (July 11, 1930 \u2013 October 14, 2019) was an American literary critic and the [[Sterling Professor]] of [[Humanities]] at [[Yale University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.yale.edu/faculty-staff/harold-bloom|title=Faculty - English|author=|date=|website=Yale University|accessdate=March 27, 2018}}</ref> He is often cited as the most influential critic of the late 20th century. Following the publication of his first book in 1959, Bloom wrote more than 50 books,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/culture/2015/04/harold-bloom-the-daemon-knows-12-authors|title=How Harold Bloom Selected His Top 12 American Authors|first=Mary Alice|last=Miller|date=|website=Vanity Fair|accessdate=March 27, 2018}}</ref> including 20 books of [[literary criticism]], several books discussing religion, and a novel. During his lifetime, he edited hundreds of anthologies concerning numerous literary and philosophical figures for the [[Chelsea House]] publishing firm.<ref name=\"chronicle.com\">{{cite journal|last=Romano |first=Carlin |url=http://chronicle.com/article/Harold-Bloom-by-the-Numbers/127211/ |title=Harold Bloom by the Numbers \u2013 The Chronicle Review  |journal=The Chronicle of Higher Education|date=April 24, 2011 |accessdate=June 25, 2013}}</ref><ref name=nytbegley /> Bloom's books have been translated into more than 40&nbsp;languages.\n\nBloom was a defender of the traditional [[Western canon]] at a time when literary departments were focusing on what he derided as the \"[[School of Resentment|school of resentment]]\" (multiculturalists, feminists, Marxists, neoconservatives, and others).<ref name=\"NYTObit\"/><ref name=\"Herman2003\">{{cite book|author=Marc Redfield|editor=Peter C. Herman|title=Historicizing Theory|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O165_qUlm5wC&pg=PA230|year=2003|publisher=Suny Press|isbn=978-0-7914-5962-1|page=210|chapter=Literature, Incorporated}}</ref> He was educated at [[Yale University]], the [[University of Cambridge]], and [[Cornell University]].\n\n==Early life==\nBloom was born in [[New York City]] on July 11, 1930,<ref name=\"NYTObit\"/> the son of Paula (n\u00e9e Lev) and William Bloom. He lived in the [[Bronx]] at 1410 [[Grand Concourse (Bronx)|Grand Concourse]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/16/nyregion/16library.html|title=New Bronx Library Meets Old Need|first=Glenn |last=Collins |work=The New York Times |date=January 16, 2006 |accessdate=February 23, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.enotes.com/topics/harold-bloom|title=Harold Bloom Biography \u2013 eNotes.com|author=|date=|website=eNotes|accessdate=March 27, 2018}}</ref> He was raised as an [[Orthodox Jew]] in a [[Yiddish]]-speaking household, where he learned literary [[Hebrew]];<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news| url=http://www.kcrw.com/etc/programs/bw/bw111020harold_bloom_the_sha |title=Harold Bloom: The Shadow of a Great Rock |work= Bookworm |publisher= KCRW}}</ref> he learned English at the age of six.<ref>{{cite news|work=The New York Times|title=New Bronx Library Meets Old Need|date= January 16, 2006 |author= Collins, Glenn| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/16/nyregion/16library.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0}}</ref> Bloom's father, a garment worker, was born in [[Odessa]] and his mother, a homemaker, near [[Brest Litovsk]] in what is today [[Belarus]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/> Harold had three older sisters and an older brother; he was the last living sibling.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n\nAs a boy, Bloom read [[Hart Crane]]'s ''Collected Poems,'' a collection that inspired his lifelong fascination with poetry.<ref>{{cite book|author= Bloom, Harold|title= The Best Poems of the English Language: From Chaucer Through Robert Frost|publisher= HarperCollins|date=2004|page=1942}}</ref> Bloom went to the [[Bronx High School of Science]] (where his grades were poor but his standardized-test scores were high),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/people/literature-and-arts/american-literature-biographies/harold-bloom|title=Harold Bloom facts, information, pictures \u2013 Encyclopedia.com articles about Harold Bloom|author=|date=|website=www.encyclopedia.com|accessdate=March 27, 2018}}</ref> and subsequently received a B.A. degree in [[Classics]] from [[Cornell University|Cornell]] in 1951, where he was a student of English literary critic [[M. H. Abrams]], and a PhD from [[Yale University|Yale]] in 1955.<ref>{{cite book |title= International Who's Who of Authors and Writers 2004 |publisher= [[Europa Publications]] |year= 2003 |edition= 19th |location= London |isbn= 978-1-85743-179-7 |page= 60 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=phhhHT64kIMC&pg=PA60 }}</ref> In 1954\u201355 Bloom was a [[Fulbright Scholar]] at [[Pembroke College, Cambridge]].<ref>Harold Bloom, \"Introduction\" in Harold Bloom (ed.), ''C.S. Lewis'' (New York: Chelsea House, 2006), p. 1.</ref>\n\nBloom was a standout student at Yale, where he clashed with the faculty of [[New Critics]] including [[William K. Wimsatt]]. Several years later, Bloom dedicated his first major book, ''[[The Anxiety of Influence]]'', to Wimsatt.<ref>{{cite news |last=Tanenhaus |first=Sam |title=Harold Bloom: An Uncommon Reader |newspaper=The New York Times |date=May 20, 2011 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/22/books/review/book-review-the-anatomy-of-influence-by-harold-bloom.html |accessdate=February 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Teaching career==\nBloom was a member of the Yale English Department from 1955 to 2019, teaching his final class four days before his death.<ref name=\"NYTObit\"/> He received a [[MacArthur Fellowship]] in 1985. From 1988 to 2004, Bloom was Berg Professor of English at [[New York University]] while maintaining his position at Yale. In 2010, he became a founding patron of [[Ralston College]], a new institution in [[Savannah, Georgia]], which focuses on primary texts.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.ralston.ac/|website=Ralston.ac|title= Collegium Ralstonianum apud Savannenses \u2013 Home}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/11/08/the-woe-is-us-books/ | work=The New York Times | first=Stanley | last=Fish | title=The Woe-Is-Us Books | date=November 8, 2010}}</ref> Fond of [[Term of endearment|endearments]], Bloom would address both male and female students and friends as \"my dear\".<ref name=\"NYTObit\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/14/books/harold-bloom-dead.html |title=Harold Bloom, Critic Who Championed Western Canon, Dies at 89 |last=Smith |first=Dinitia |date=October 14, 2019 |work=The New York Times |access-date=October 14, 2019 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life and death==\nBloom married Jeanne Gould in 1958.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2012/feb/23/grand-comedian-visits-bible/?pagination=false |title=The Grand Comedian Visits the Bible by Harold Bloom  |journal=The New York Review of Books |publisher=Nybooks.com |date=February 23, 2012 |accessdate=June 25, 2013}}</ref> They had two children.<ref name=\"latimesobit\">{{cite web|url =https://www.latimes.com/obituaries/story/2019-10-14/harold-bloom-dead|title =Harold Bloom, author of \u2018Anxiety of Influence\u2019 who fought modern trends, dies at 89|first =Elaine|last =Woo|website =Los Angeles Times|date =October 14, 2019}}</ref> In a 2005 interview Jeanne said that she and Harold were both [[atheist]]s, which he denied: \"No, no I'm not an atheist. It's no fun being an atheist.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rc.umd.edu/praxis/bloom_hartman/bloom/bloom.html|title=An Interview with Harold Bloom|first=Quinney|last= Laura|date=November 27, 2005|website=Romantic Circles|accessdate=March 27, 2018|publisher=University of Colorado Boulder}}</ref>\n\nBloom was the subject of a 1990 article in ''[[GQ]]'' titled \"Bloom in Love\", which accused him of having affairs with female graduate students. Bloom described the article as a \"disgusting piece of character assassination\". Bloom's friend and colleague, the biographer [[R. W. B. Lewis]] said in 1994 that \"[Bloom's] wandering, I gather is a thing of the past. I hate to say it, but he rather bragged about it, so that wasn't very secret for a number of years.\"<ref>Begley, Adam. [https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/books/98/11/01/specials/bloom-colossus.html \"Colossus Among Critics: Harold Bloom\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', September 25, 1994. Retrieved on October 15, 2019.</ref> In a 2004 article for ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine, [[Naomi Wolf]] accused Bloom of placing his hand on her inner thigh while she was an undergraduate student at Yale University in 1983.<ref name=\"Wolf2004\">{{cite magazine|author=Naomi Wolf|title=The Silent Treatment|url=http://nymag.com/nymetro/news/features/n_9932/|year=2004|magazine=New York Magazine}}</ref> Bloom \"vigorously denied\" the allegation.<ref name=\"NYTObit\"/><ref name=\"Time\">{{Cite magazine|last=D'addario|first=Daniel|date=May 11, 2015|title=10 Questions with Harold Bloom|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time Magazine]]}}</ref>\n\nBloom taught well into his later years, swearing that he would need to be removed from the classroom \"in a great big body bag\". He had open heart surgery in 2002 and broke his back after experiencing a fall in 2008.<ref name=latimesobit/> He died at a hospital in [[New Haven, Connecticut]], on October 14, 2019. He was 89 years old.<ref name=\"NYTObit\"/>\n\n==Writing career==\n{{More citations needed|section|date=October 2019}}\n\n===Defense of Romanticism===\nBloom began his career with a sequence of highly regarded monographs on [[Percy Bysshe Shelley]] (''Shelley's Myth-making'', [[Yale University Press]], originally Bloom's doctoral dissertation),<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hartman |first1=Geoffrey H. |title=Criticism in the Wilderness: The Study of Literature Today |date=2007 |publisher=Yale University Press |isbn=9780300123982 |page=102 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=qSbJWWn8sRUC |accessdate= October 16, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> [[W. B. Yeats]] (''Yeats'', [[Oxford University Press]]),<ref>{{cite web |title=YEATS by Harold Bloom |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/harold-bloom/yeats/ |website=[[Kirkus Reviews|www.kirkusreviews.com]] |date= July 21, 2019|accessdate=16 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref> and [[Wallace Stevens]] (''Wallace Stevens: The Poems of Our Climate'', [[Cornell University Press]]).<ref>{{cite web |title=Wallace Stevens: The Poems of Our Climate |url=https://www.cornellpress.cornell.edu/book/9780801491856/wallace-stevens/ |publisher=Cornell University Press |accessdate= October 16, 2019}}</ref> In these, he defended the High Romantics against [[Christianity|neo-Christian]] critics influenced by such writers as [[T. S. Eliot]], who became a recurring intellectual foil. Bloom had a contentious approach: his first book, ''Shelley's Myth-making'', charged many contemporary critics with sheer carelessness in their reading of the poet.\n\n===Influence theory===\n\n[[File:Lion-faced deity.jpg|thumb|A lion-faced [[deity]] associated with [[Gnosticism]]. Bloom frequently referred to Gnosticism when speaking about general and personal religious matters.]]\n\nAfter a personal crisis during the late 1960s, Bloom became deeply interested in [[Ralph Waldo Emerson]], [[Sigmund Freud]], and the ancient mystic traditions of [[Gnosticism]], [[Kabbalah]], and [[Hermeticism]]. In a 2003 interview with Bloom, [[Michael Pakenham]], the book editor for ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'', posited that Bloom has long referred to himself as a \"Jewish Gnostic\". Bloom explained: \"I am using Gnostic in a very broad way. I am nothing if not Jewish... I really am a product of Yiddish culture. But I can't understand a [[Yahweh]], or a [[God]], who could be all-powerful and all knowing and would allow the [[Nazi death camps]] and [[schizophrenia]].\"<ref>{{cite web\n  |title = In Full Bloom: Guerrilla In Our Midst\n  |last = Pakenham\n  |first = Michael\n  |website = [[The Baltimore Sun]]\n  |date = March 23, 2003\n  |accessdate = September 15, 2016\n  |url = http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2003-03-23/entertainment/0303240442_1_bloom-dining-room-table\n  |ref = harv\n}}</ref> Influenced by his reading, he began a series of books that focused on the way in which poets struggled to create their own individual poetic visions without being overcome by the influence of the previous poets who inspired them to write.\n\nThe first of these books, ''Yeats'', a magisterial examination of [[William Butler Yeats|the poet]], challenged the conventional critical view of his poetic career. In the introduction to this volume, Bloom set out the basic principles of his new approach to criticism: \"Poetic influence, as I conceive it, is a variety of melancholy or the anxiety-principle.\" New poets become inspired to write because they have read and admired the poetry of previous poets; but this admiration turns into resentment when the new poets discover that these poets whom they idolized have already said everything they wish to say. The poets become disappointed because they \"cannot be [[Adam]] early in the morning. There have been too many Adams, and they have named everything.\"{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nIn order to evade this psychological obstacle, according to Bloom, new poets must be convinced that previous poets have gone wrong somewhere and failed in their vision, thus leaving open the possibility that they may have something to add to the tradition after all. The new poets' love for their heroes turns into antagonism towards them: \"Initial love for the precursor's poetry is transformed rapidly enough into revisionary strife, without which individuation is not possible.\"<ref>''Map of Misreading'', p. 10.</ref> The book that followed ''Yeats'', ''[[The Anxiety of Influence]]'', which Bloom had started writing in 1967, drew upon the example of [[Walter Jackson Bate]]'s ''The Burden of the Past and The English Poet'' and recast in systematic psychoanalytic form Bate's historicized account of the despair felt by 17th and 18th-century poets about their ability to match the achievements of their predecessors. Bloom attempted to trace the psychological process by which poets broke free from their precursors to achieve their own poetic vision. He drew a sharp distinction between \"strong poets\" who perform \"strong misreadings\" of their precursors, and \"weak poets\" who simply repeat the ideas of their precursors as though following a kind of doctrine. He described this process in terms of a sequence of \"revisionary ratios\", through which each strong poet passes in the course of their career.\n\n====Addenda and developments of his theory====\n''A Map of Misreading'' picked up where ''The Anxiety of Influence'' left off, making several adjustments to Bloom's system of revisionary ratios. ''Kabbalah and Criticism'' attempted to invoke the esoteric interpretive system of the [[Lurianic Kabbalah]], as explicated by scholar [[Gershom Scholem]], as an alternate system of mapping the path of poetic influence. ''Figures of Capable Imagination'' collected odd pieces Bloom had written in the process of composing his \"influence\" books.\n\nBloom continued to write about influence theory throughout the 1970s and '80s, and penned little thereafter that did not invoke his ideas about influence.\n\n===Novel experiment===\nBloom's fascination with the fantasy novel ''[[A Voyage to Arcturus]]'' by [[David Lindsay (novelist)|David Lindsay]] led him to take a brief break from criticism in order to compose a sequel to Lindsay's novel. This novel, ''[[The Flight to Lucifer]]'', was Bloom's only work of fiction.<ref name=\"The Violet Apple\">{{cite web|url=http://www.violetapple.org.uk/notes/bloom_flighttolucifer.php|title=The Flight to Lucifer review|accessdate=September 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Religious criticism===\nBloom then entered a phase of what he called \"religious criticism\", beginning with ''Ruin the Sacred Truths: Poetry and Belief from the Bible to the Present'' (1989).\n\nIn ''The Book of J'' (1990), he and [[David Rosenberg (poet)|David Rosenberg]] (who translated the Biblical texts) portrayed one of the posited ancient documents that formed the basis of the first five books of the Bible (see [[documentary hypothesis]]) as the work of a great literary artist who had no intention of composing a [[dogmatic]]ally religious work (see [[Jahwist]]). They further envisaged this anonymous writer as a woman attached to the court of the successors of the Israelite kings [[David]] and [[King Solomon|Solomon]]\u2014a piece of speculation which drew much attention. Later, Bloom said that the speculations did not go far enough, and perhaps he should have identified J with the Biblical [[Bathsheba]].<ref>Bloom, Harold, ''The Western Canon. The Books and Schools of the Ages'', New York: Harcourt Brace & Company, 1994, p. 5.</ref> In ''Jesus and Yahweh: The Names Divine'' (2004), he revisits some of the territory he covered in ''The Book of J'' in discussing the significance of [[YHWH|Yahweh]] and [[Jesus of Nazareth]] as literary characters, while casting a critical eye on historical approaches and asserting the fundamental incompatibility of [[Christianity and Judaism]].\n\nIn ''[[The American Religion]]'' (1992), Bloom surveyed the major varieties of [[Protestant]] and post-Protestant religious faiths that originated in the United States and argued that, in terms of their psychological hold on their adherents, most shared more in common with [[gnosticism]] than with historical Christianity. The exception was the [[Jehovah's Witnesses]], whom Bloom regards as non-Gnostic. He elsewhere predicted that the [[Mormon]] and [[Pentecostal]] strains of [[American Christianity]] would overtake mainstream Protestant divisions in popularity in the next few decades. In ''Omens of Millennium'' (1996), Bloom identifies these American religious elements as on the periphery of an old \u2013 and not inherently Christian \u2013 gnostic, religious tradition which invokes a complex of ideas and experiences concerning [[angelology]], interpretation of dreams as [[prophecy]], [[near-death experience]]s, and [[millennialism]].<ref>Bloom (1996), p. 5.</ref>\n\nIn his essay in ''The Gospel of Thomas'', Bloom states that none of Thomas' [[Aramaic]] sayings have survived in the original language.<ref>Bloom, Harold. \"A Reading\", in ''The Gospel of Thomas: The Hidden Sayings of Jesus''. English translation and critical edition of the Coptic text by Marvin W. Meyer. San Francisco: HarperSanFrancisco, 1992, pp. 115 and 119.</ref> [[Marvin Meyer]] generally agreed and further confirmed that the earlier versions of that text were likely written in either Aramaic or Greek.<ref>Mayer, Marvin. \"Introduction\". The Gospel of Thomas. San Francisco: HarperSanFrancisco, 1992, p. 9.</ref> Meyer ends his introduction with an endorsement of much of Bloom's essay.<ref>Meyer (1992), p. 19.</ref> Bloom notes the other-worldliness of the Jesus in the Thomas sayings by making reference to \"the paradox also of the American Jesus.\"<ref>Meyer (1992), p. 119.</ref>\n\n===''The Western Canon''===\n''[[The Western Canon]]'' (1994), a survey of the major literary works of Europe and the Americas since the 14th century, focuses on 26 works he considered sublime and representative of their nations<ref>Bloom (1994), p. 2.</ref> and of the [[Western canon]].<ref>Bloom (1994), p. 11.</ref> Besides analyses of the canon's various representative works, Bloom's major concern in the volume was reclaiming literature from those he referred to as the \"[[School of Resentment]]\", the mostly academic critics who espoused a social purpose in reading. Bloom asserted that the goals of reading must be solitary [[aesthetic]] pleasure and self-insight rather than the goal of improving one's society held by \"forces of resentment\". He cast the latter as an absurd aim, writing: \"The idea that you benefit the insulted and injured by reading someone of their own origins rather than reading [[Shakespeare]] is one of the oddest illusions ever promoted by or in our schools.\" His position was that politics had no place in literary criticism, that a [[feminist]] or [[Marxist]] reading of ''[[Hamlet]]'' would tell us something about feminism and Marxism but probably nothing about ''Hamlet'' itself.\n\nIn addition to considering how much influence a writer had had on later writers, Bloom proposed the concept of \"canonical strangeness\" (cf. [[uncanny]]) as a benchmark of a literary work's merit. ''The Western Canon'' also included a list\u2014which aroused more widespread interest than anything else in the volume\u2014of all the Western works from antiquity to the present that Bloom considered either permanent members of the canon of literary classics, or (among more recent works) candidates for that status. Bloom said that he made the list off the top of his head at his editor's request, and that he did not stand by it.<ref name=vice />\n\n===Work on Shakespeare===\n[[File:Shakespeare.jpg|thumb|[[William Shakespeare]] (1564\u20131616)]]\n\nBloom had a deep appreciation for [[William Shakespeare]]<ref>Bloom (1994), pp.&nbsp;2\u20133.</ref> and considered him to be the supreme center of the Western canon.<ref>Bloom (1994), pp.&nbsp;24\u20135.</ref> The first edition of ''The Anxiety of Influence'' almost completely avoided Shakespeare, whom Bloom then considered barely touched by the psychological drama of anxiety. The second edition, published in 1997, added a long preface that mostly expounded Shakespeare's debt to [[Ovid]] and [[Geoffrey Chaucer|Chaucer]], and his [[agon#Literature|agon]] with contemporary [[Christopher Marlowe]], who set the stage for him by breaking free of ecclesiastical and moralizing overtones.\n\nIn his later survey, ''Shakespeare: The Invention of the Human'' (1998), Bloom provided an analysis of each of Shakespeare's 38 plays, \"twenty-four of which are masterpieces.\" Written as a companion to the general reader and theater-goer, Bloom declared that [[bardolatry]] \"ought to be even more a secular religion than it already is.\"<ref>Bloom, Harold. ''Shakespeare: The Invention of the Human''. New York: Riverhead, 1998, p. xix.</ref> He also contended in the work (as in the title) that Shakespeare \"invented\" humanity, in that he prescribed the now-common practice of \"overhearing\" ourselves, which drives our changes. The two paragons of his theory were [[Sir John Falstaff]] of ''[[Henry IV, Part 1|Henry IV]]'' and [[Prince Hamlet|Hamlet]], whom Bloom saw as representing self-satisfaction and self-loathing, respectively. Throughout ''Shakespeare'', characters from disparate plays were imagined alongside and interacting with each other. This has been decried by numerous contemporary academics and critics as harking back to the out of fashion character criticism of [[A. C. Bradley]] (and others), who gathered explicit praise in the book. As in ''The Western Canon'', Bloom criticized what he called the \"School of Resentment\" for its failure to live up to the challenge of Shakespeare's universality and for [[Balkanization|balkanizing]] the study of literature through multicultural and [[New Historicism|historicist]] departments. Asserting Shakespeare's singular popularity throughout the world, Bloom proclaimed him the only truly multicultural author. Repudiating the \"social energies\" to which historicists ascribed Shakespeare's authorship, Bloom pronounced his modern academic foes \u2013 and indeed, all of society \u2013 to be but \"a parody of Shakespearian energies.\"\n\n===2000s and 2010s===\nBloom consolidated his work on the western canon with the publication of ''How to Read and Why'' (2000) and ''Genius: A Mosaic of One Hundred Exemplary Creative Minds'' (2003). ''Hamlet: Poem Unlimited'' (also 2003) is an amendment to ''Shakespeare: Invention of the Human'' written after he decided the chapter on ''Hamlet'' in that earlier book had been too focused on the textual question of the ''[[Ur-Hamlet]]'' to cover his most central thoughts on the play itself. Some elements of religious criticism were combined with his secular criticism in ''Where Shall Wisdom Be Found'' (2004), and a more complete return to religious criticism was marked by the publication of ''Jesus and Yahweh: The Names Divine'' (2005). Throughout the decade he also compiled, edited and introduced several major anthologies of poetry.\n\nBloom took part in the documentary, the ''[[Apparition of the Eternal Church]]'' (2006), made by [[Paul Festa]]. This documentary centered on many individuals' reactions to hearing, for the first time, Olivier Messiaen's organ piece ''[[Apparition de l'\u00e9glise \u00e9ternelle]]''.\n\nBloom began a book under the working title of ''Living Labyrinth'', centering on Shakespeare and [[Walt Whitman]], which was published as ''The Anatomy of Influence: Literature as a Way of Life'' (2011).\n\nIn July 2011, after the publication of ''The Anatomy of Influence'' and after finishing work on ''The Shadow of a Great Rock'', Bloom was working on three further projects:\n* ''Achievement in the Evening Land from Emerson to [[Faulkner]]'', a history of American literature following the canonical model, which ultimately developed into his book ''The Daemon Knows: Literary Greatness and the American Sublime'' (2015).\n* ''The Hum of Thoughts Evaded in the Mind: A Literary Memoir'', which ultimately developed into his book ''Possessed by Memory: The Inward Light of Criticism'' (2019).\n* a play with the working title ''Walt Whitman: A Musical Pageant''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radioopensource.org/harold-bloom-on-the-playing-field-of-poetry/|title=Harold Bloom: On the Playing Field of Poetry - Open Source with Christopher Lydon|author=|date=July 5, 2011|website=www.radioopensource.org|accessdate=March 27, 2018}}</ref> By November 2011, Bloom had changed the title of the play to ''To You Whoever You Are: A Pageant Celebrating Walt Whitman''.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/13/opinion/sunday/will-this-election-be-the-mormon-breakthrough.html \"Will This Election Be the Mormon Breakthrough?\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', November 12, 2011.</ref>\n\n==Influence==\n[[File:Samuel Johnson by Joshua Reynolds.jpg|thumb|In ''[[The Western Canon: The Books and School of the Ages|The Western Canon]]'', Bloom claimed that [[Samuel Johnson]] was \"unmatched by any critic in any nation before or after him.\"]]\n\nIn 1986, Bloom credited [[Northrop Frye]] as his nearest precursor. He told [[Imre Salusinszky]] in 1986: \"In terms of my own theorizations&nbsp;... the precursor proper has to be Northrop Frye. I purchased and read ''[[Fearful Symmetry (Frye)|Fearful Symmetry]]'' a week or two after it had come out and reached the bookstore in Ithaca, New York. It ravished my heart away. I have tried to find an alternative father in Mr. [[Kenneth Burke]], who is a charming fellow and a very powerful critic, but I don't come from Burke, I come out of Frye.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prelectur.stanford.edu/lecturers/bloom/interviews.html#roots|title=Presidential Lectures: Harold Bloom: Interviews|author=|date=|website=prelectur.stanford.edu|accessdate=March 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHowever, in ''Anatomy of Influence'' (2011), he wrote \"I no longer have the patience to read anything by Frye\" and nominated Angus Fletcher of the City University of New York among his living contemporaries as his \"critical guide and conscience\" and elsewhere that year recommended Fletcher's ''Colors of the Mind'' and ''The Mirror and the Lamp'' by [[M. H. Abrams]]. In this late phase of his career, Bloom also emphasized the tradition of earlier critics such as [[William Hazlitt]], Ralph Waldo Emerson, [[Walter Pater]], [[A. C. Bradley]], and [[Samuel Johnson]], describing Johnson in ''The Western Canon'' as \"unmatched by any critic in any nation before or after him\". In his 2012 Foreword to the book ''The Fourth Dimension of a Poem'' (WW Norton, 2012), Bloom indicated the influence which M. H. Abrams had upon him in his years at Cornell University.<ref>M. H. Abrams. ''The Fourth Dimension of a Poem'' (WW Norton, 2012).</ref>\n\nBloom's theory of poetic influence regards the development of [[Western literature]] as a process of borrowing and misreading. Writers find their creative inspiration in previous writers and begin by imitating those writers in order to develop a poetic voice of their own; however, they must make their own work different from that of their precursors. As a result, Bloom argues, authors of real power must inevitably \"misread\" their precursors' works in order to make room for fresh imaginings.<ref>{{cite journal| url=http://www.theparisreview.org/interviews/2225/the-art-of-criticism-no-1-harold-bloom| title=Harold Bloom, The Art of Criticism No. 1| journal=Paris Review| volume=Spring 1991| issue=118| date=Spring 1991| author=Antonio Weiss}}</ref><ref>Paul Fry, [http://oyc.yale.edu/english/engl-300/lecture-14 \"Engl 300: Introduction To Theory Of Literature\"]. Lecture 14 \u2013 Influence. Open Yale lectures on the influence of Bloom and Eliot.</ref>\n\nObservers often identified Bloom with [[deconstruction]] in the past, but he himself never admitted to sharing more than a few ideas with the deconstructionists. He told [[Robert Moynihan]] in 1983, \"What I think I have in common with the school of deconstruction is the mode of negative thinking or negative awareness, in the technical, philosophical sense of the negative, but which comes to me through [[apophatic theology|negative theology]]&nbsp;... There is no escape, there is simply the given, and there is nothing that we can do.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview with Harold Bloom|url=https://prelectur.stanford.edu/lecturers/bloom/interviews.html|work=Stanford Presidential Lectures in the Humanities and Arts|publisher=Stanford University|accessdate=March 15, 2014}} Excerpted from \"Interview: Harold Bloom interviewed by Robert Moynihan\" ''Diacritics : A Review of Contemporary Criticism'' vol. 13 , No. 3 (Fall, 1983), pp. 57\u201368.</ref>\n\nBloom's association with the [[Western canon]] provoked a substantial interest in his opinion concerning the relative importance of contemporary writers. In the late 1980s, Bloom told an interviewer: \"Probably the most powerful living Western writer is [[Samuel Beckett]]. He's certainly the most authentic.\"<ref>[http://new.bostonreview.net/BR11.1/bloom.html \"Candidates for Survival: A talk with Harold Bloom\"], ''Boston Review'', February, 1989; {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140315224424/http://new.bostonreview.net/BR11.1/bloom.html |date=March 15, 2014 }}</ref> After Beckett died in 1989, Bloom pointed towards other authors as the new main figures of the Western literary canon.\n\nConcerning British writers: \"[[Geoffrey Hill]] is the strongest British poet now active\", and \"no other contemporary British novelist seems to me to be of [[Iris Murdoch]]'s eminence\". After Murdoch died, Bloom expressed admiration for novelists such as [[Peter Ackroyd]], [[Will Self]], [[John Banville]], and [[A. S. Byatt]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Bloom|first=Harold|title=Genius : a mosaic of one hundred exemplary creative minds|year=2002|publisher=Warner Books|location=New York|isbn=0-446-69129-1|page=648|quote=There are a few affinities, except perhaps with the admirable Antonia Byatt, in the generation after: novelists I also now admire, like Will Self, Peter Ackroyd, and John Banville.}}</ref>\n\nIn ''Genius: A Mosaic of One Hundred Exemplary Creative Minds'' (2003), he named the [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]] writer and Nobel Prize winner [[Jos\u00e9 Saramago]] as \"the most gifted novelist alive in the world today\", and as \"one of the last titans of an expiring literary genre\".\n\nOf American novelists, he declared in 2003 that \"there are four living American novelists I know of who are still at work and who deserve our praise\".<ref>[http://www.boston.com/news/globe/editorial_opinion/oped/articles/2003/09/24/dumbing_down_american_readers/ \"Dumbing Down American Readers\"], ''Boston Globe'', September 24, 2003. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060617015302/http://www.boston.com/news/globe/editorial_opinion/oped/articles/2003/09/24/dumbing_down_american_readers/ |date=June 17, 2006 }}</ref> He claimed that \"they write the Style of our Age, each has composed canonical works,\" and he identified them as [[Thomas Pynchon]], [[Philip Roth]], [[Cormac McCarthy]], and [[Don DeLillo]]. He named their strongest works as, respectively, ''[[Gravity's Rainbow]]'', ''[[The Crying of Lot 49]]'' and ''[[Mason & Dixon]]''; ''[[American Pastoral]]'' and ''[[Sabbath's Theater]]''; ''[[Blood Meridian]]''; and ''[[Underworld (DeLillo novel)|Underworld]]''. He added to this estimate the work of [[John Crowley (author)|John Crowley]], with special interest in his [[Aegypt Sequence]] and novel ''[[Little, Big]]'' saying that \"only a handful of living writers in English can equal him as a stylist, and most of them are poets&nbsp;... only Philip Roth consistently writes on Crowley's level\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Bloom|first=Harold|title=Snake's-hands : the fiction of John Crowley|year=2003|publisher=Cosmos Books|location=[Canton, OH]|isbn=1-58715-509-5|page=10|url=https://books.google.com/?id=JsaIP2n6xvgC&printsec=frontcover&dq=old+snake-hands#v=onepage&q=Crowley%20Roth&f=false|chapter=Preface}}</ref>\n\nIn ''Kabbalah and Criticism'' (1975), Bloom identified [[Robert Penn Warren]], [[James Merrill]], [[John Ashbery]], and [[Elizabeth Bishop]] as the most important living American poets. By the 1990s, he regularly named [[A. R. Ammons]] along with Ashbery and Merrill, and he later identified [[Henri Cole]] as the crucial American poet of the generation following those three. He expressed great admiration for the Canadian poets [[Anne Carson]], particularly her [[verse novel]] ''Autobiography of Red,'' and [[A. F. Moritz]], whom Bloom called \"a true poet.\"<ref>{{Citation | last=Hollander|first=John|authorlink=John Hollander|contribution=Enriching Shadow: A.F. Moritz's Early Poems|editor-last=Moritz|editor-first=A.F.|title=Early Poems|pages=17|publisher=Insomniac Press|place=Toronto|year=2002|url=https://books.google.com/?id=owHzhPCAEv8C&pg=PA17&lpg=PA17&dq=bloom+%22true+poet%22#v=onepage&q=moritz%20bloom%20%22true%20poet%22&f=false|isbn=9781897414774}}</ref> Bloom also listed [[Jay Wright (poet)|Jay Wright]] as one of only a handful of major living poets.<ref>Harold Bloom (ed.), ''Modern Critical Interpretations: Jay Wright'', New York: Chelsea House, 2003.</ref>\n\nBloom's introduction to ''Modern Critical Interpretations: Thomas Pynchon's Gravity's Rainbow'' (1986) features his canon of the \"twentieth-century American Sublime\", the greatest works of American art produced in the 20th century. Playwright [[Tony Kushner]] sees Bloom as an important influence on his work.<ref>Harold Bloom (ed.), ''Modern Critical Interpretations: Thomas Pynchon's Gravity's Rainbow'', New York: Chelsea House, 1986.</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nFor many years, Bloom's writings have drawn polarized responses, even among established literary scholars. Bloom was called \"probably the most celebrated literary critic in the United States\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2002/oct/12/featuresreviews.guardianreview14 | location=London | work=[[The Guardian]] | first=Frank | last=Kermode| authorlink = Frank Kermode | title=Review: Genius by Harold Bloom | date=October 12, 2002}}</ref> and \"America's best-known man of letters\".<ref name=\"powells1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.powells.com/review/2006_05_11.html?&PID=18|title=Powell's Books - The World's Largest Independent Bookstore|first=Used, New, and Out of Print Books - We Buy and Sell - Powell's|last=Books|date=|website=www.powells.com|accessdate=March 27, 2018}}</ref> A ''[[New York Times]]'' article in 1994 said that many younger critics understand Bloom as an \"outdated oddity,\"<ref name=\"nytbegley\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/11/01/specials/bloom-colossus.html | location=New York | work=[[The New York Times]] | first=Adam | last=Begley| authorlink = Adam Begley| title=Review: Colossus Among Critics: Harold Bloom | date=September 24, 1994}}</ref> whereas a 1998 ''New York Times'' article called him \"one of the most gifted of contemporary critics.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/11/01/reviews/981101.01shapirt.html | location=New York | work=[[The New York Times]] | first=James | last=Shapiro| title=Soul of the Age | date=November 1, 1998}}</ref>\n\n[[James Wood (critic)|James Wood]] described Bloom as \"Vatic, repetitious, imprecisely reverential, though never without a peculiar charm of his own\u2014a kind of campiness, in fact\u2014Bloom as a literary critic in the last few years has been largely unimportant.\"<ref name=\"powells1\"/> Bloom responded to questions about Wood in an interview by saying: \"There are period pieces in criticism as there are period pieces in the novel and in poetry. The wind blows and they will go away&nbsp;... There's nothing to the man&nbsp;... I don't want to talk about him\".<ref name=\"vice\">{{cite web|last=Pearson |first=Jesse | authorlink =Jesse Pearson (writer)|url=https://www.vice.com/read/harold-bloom-431-v15n12 |title=Harold Bloom |work=[[VICE United States]] |date=December 2, 2008 |accessdate=June 25, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014172844/http://www.vice.com/read/harold-bloom-431-v15n12 |archive-date=October 14, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 21st century, Bloom often found himself at the center of literary controversy after criticizing popular writers such as [[Adrienne Rich]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://new.bostonreview.net/BR23.3/perloff.html |title=Visionary Company|website=Boston Review|access-date=September 23, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925070808/http://new.bostonreview.net/BR23.3/perloff.html |archive-date=September 25, 2015 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> [[Maya Angelou]],<ref>\"Miss [[Maya Angelou]] cannot write her way out of a paper bag!\"\nKenton Robinson, \"Foe To Those Who Would Shape Literature To Their Own End Dissent in Bloom\" ''[[Hartford Courant]]'' October 4, 1994 E.1</ref> and [[David Foster Wallace]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Koski|first=Lorna|title=The Full Harold Bloom|url=http://www.wwd.com/eye/people/the-full-bloom-3592315?full=true|accessdate=October 19, 2012|newspaper=[[Women's Wear Daily]]|date=April 26, 2011}}</ref> In the pages of ''[[The Paris Review]]'', he criticized the [[populism|populist]]-leaning [[poetry slam]], saying: \"It is the death of art.\" When [[Doris Lessing]] was awarded the [[Nobel Prize in Literature]], he bemoaned the \"pure political correctness\" of the award to an author of \"fourth-rate science fiction,\" although he conceded his appreciation of Lessing's earlier work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.today.com/id/12784353|agency=Associated Press|title=U.K.'s Lessing wins Nobel Prize in literature|author=|date=October 11, 2007|website=msn.com|accessdate=March 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMormonVoices, a group associated with [[FairMormon|Foundation for Apologetic Information & Research]], included Bloom on its Top Ten Anti-Mormon Statements of 2011 list for stating \"The current head of the Mormon Church, [[Thomas S. Monson]], known to his followers as 'prophet, seer and revelator,' is indistinguishable from the secular plutocratic oligarchs who exercise power in our supposed democracy\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/print/700213557/Group-lists-Top-Ten-Anti-Mormon-Statements-of-2011.html |title=Group lists Top Ten Anti-Mormon Statements of 2011 |date=January 8, 2012 |work=[[Deseret News]] |first=Joseph |last=Walker}}</ref>\n\n==Selected bibliography==\n\n===Books===\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* ''Shelley's Mythmaking.'' New Haven: Yale University Press, 1959.\n* ''The Visionary Company: A Reading of English Romantic Poetry.'' Garden City, N.Y.: Doubleday, 1961. Revised and enlarged edn. Ithaca: Cornell University Press, 1971.\n* ''Blake's Apocalypse: A Study in Poetic Argument.'' Anchor Books: New York: Doubleday and Co., 1963.\n* ''The Literary Criticism of John Ruskin.''; edited with introduction. New York: DoubleDay, 1965.\n* ''Walter Pater: Marius the Epicurean''; edition with introduction. New York: New American Library, 1970.\n* ''Romanticism and Consciousness: Essays in Criticism.''; edited with introduction. New York: Norton, 1970.\n* ''Yeats.'' New York: Oxford University Press, 1970. {{ISBN|0-19-501603-3}}\n* ''The Ringers in the Tower: Studies in Romantic Tradition.'' Chicago: University of Chicago Press, 1971.\n* ''[[The Anxiety of Influence|The Anxiety of Influence: A Theory of Poetry]]''. New York: Oxford University Press, 1973; 2nd edn, 1997. {{ISBN|0-19-511221-0}}\n* ''The Selected Writings of Walter Pater''; edition with introduction and notes. New York: New American Library, 1974.\n* ''A Map of Misreading.'' New York: Oxford University Press, 1975.\n* ''Kabbalah and Criticism.'' New York : Seabury Press, 1975. {{ISBN|0-8264-0242-9}}\n* ''Poetry and Repression: Revisionism from Blake to Stevens.'' New Haven: Yale University Press, 1976.\n* ''Figures of Capable Imagination.'' New York: Seabury Press, 1976.\n* ''Wallace Stevens: The Poems of our Climate.'' Ithaca, N.Y.: Cornell University Press, 1977.\n* ''Deconstruction and Criticism.'' New York: Seabury Press, 1980.\n* ''[[The Flight to Lucifer|The Flight to Lucifer: A Gnostic Fantasy]].'' New York: Vintage Books, 1980. {{ISBN|0-394-74323-7}}\n* ''Agon: Towards a Theory of Revisionism.'' New York : Oxford University Press, 1982.\n* ''The Breaking of the Vessels.'' Chicago: University of Chicago Press, 1982.\n* ''The Poetics of Influence: New and Selected Criticism.'' New Haven: Henry R. Schwab, 1988.\n* ''Ruin the Sacred Truths: Poetry and Belief from the Bible to the Present.'' Cambridge, Mass.: Harvard University Press, 1989.\n* ''The Book of J: Translated from the Hebrew by David Rosenberg; Interpreted by Harold Bloom.'' New York: Grove Press, 1990 {{ISBN|0-8021-4191-9}}\n* ''The Gospel of Thomas: The Hidden Sayings of Jesus''; translation with introduction, critical edition of the Coptic text and notes by Marvin Meyer, with an interpretation by Harold Bloom. San Francisco: HarperSanFrancisco, 1992.\n* ''[[The American Religion: The Emergence of the Post-Christian Nation]]''; Touchstone Books; {{ISBN|0-671-86737-7}} (1992; August 1993)\n* ''[[The Western Canon (book)|The Western Canon: The Books and School of the Ages]]''. New York: Harcourt Brace, 1994.\n* ''Omens of Millennium: The Gnosis of Angels, Dreams, and Resurrection.'' New York: Riverhead Books, 1996.\n* ''[[Shakespeare: The Invention of the Human]].'' New York: 1998. {{ISBN|1-57322-751-X}}\n* ''How to Read and Why.'' New York: 2000. {{ISBN|0-684-85906-8}}\n* ''Stories and Poems for Extremely Intelligent Children of All Ages.'' New York: 2001.\n* ''El futur de la imaginaci\u00f3 (The Future of the Imagination).'' Barcelona: [[Anagrama]] / Emp\u00faries, 2002. {{ISBN|84-7596-927-5}}\n* ''[[Genius: A Mosaic of One Hundred Exemplary Creative Minds]].'' New York: 2003. {{ISBN|0-446-52717-3}}\n* ''Hamlet: Poem Unlimited''. New York: 2003.\n* ''The Best Poems of the English Language: From Chaucer Through Frost.'' New York: 2004. {{ISBN|0-06-054041-9}}\n* ''Where Shall Wisdom Be Found?'' New York: 2004. {{ISBN|1-57322-284-4}}\n* ''[[Jesus and Yahweh: The Names Divine]]''. 2005. {{ISBN|1-57322-322-0}}\n* ''American Religious Poems: An Anthology By Harold Bloom''. 2006. {{ISBN|1-931082-74-X}}\n* ''Fallen Angels'', illustrated by Mark Podwal. Yale University Press, 2007. {{ISBN|0-300-12348-5}}\n* ''Till I End My Song: A Gathering of Last Poems'' Harper, 2010. {{ISBN|0-06-192305-2}}\n* ''[[The Anatomy of Influence: Literature as a Way of Life]]''. Yale University Press, 2011. {{ISBN|0-300-16760-1}}\n* ''The Shadow of a Great Rock: A Literary Appreciation of The King James Bible''. Yale University Press, 2011. {{ISBN|0-300-16683-4}}\n* ''The Daemon Knows: Literary Greatness and the American Sublime''. Spiegel & Grau, 2015. {{ISBN|0-812-99782-4}}\n* ''Falstaff: Give Me Life''. Scribner, 2017. {{ISBN|978-1-5011-6413-2}}\n* ''Cleopatra: I Am Fire and Air''. Scribner, 2017. {{ISBN|978-1-5011-6416-3}}\n* ''Lear: The Great Image of Authority''. Scribner, 2018. {{ISBN|978-1-5011-6419-4}}\n* ''Iago: The Strategies of Evil''. Scribner, 2018. {{ISBN|978-1-5011-6422-4}}\n* ''Macbeth: A Dagger of the Mind''. Scribner, 2019. {{ISBN|978-1-5011-6425-5}}\n* ''Possessed by Memory: The Inward Light of Criticism''. Knopf, 2019. {{ISBN|978-0-5255-2088-7}}\n{{refend}}\n\n===Articles===\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/12/21/home/stevens-vendler.html \"On Extended Wings\"]; Wallace Stevens' Longer Poems. By Helen Hennessy Vendler, (Review), ''[[The New York Times]]'', October 5, 1969.\n* \"Poets' meeting in the heyday of their youth; A Single Summer With Lord Byron\", ''The New York Times'', February 15, 1970.\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/1970/11/22/archives/an-angels-spirit-in-a-decaying-and-active-body.html \"An angel's spirit in a decaying (and active) body\"], ''The New York Times'', November 22, 1970.\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/1975/11/12/archives/the-use-of-poetry.html \"The Use of Poetry\"], ''The New York Times'', November 12, 1975.\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/1976/04/18/archives/northrop-frye-exalting-the-designs-of-romance-the-secular-scripture.html \"Northrop Frye exalting the designs of romance; The Secular Scripture\"], ''The New York Times'', April 18, 1976.\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/1977/08/04/archives/on-solitude-in-america.html \"On Solitude in America\"], ''The New York Times'', August 4, 1977.\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/1978/02/05/archives/the-criticpoet.html \"The Critic/Poet\"], ''The New York Times'', February 5, 1978.\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/1979/07/22/archives/a-fusion-of-traditions-rosenberg.html \"A Fusion of Traditions: The Collected Works of Isaac Rosenberg\"], ''The New York Times'', July 22, 1979.\n* \"Straight Forth Out of Self\", ''The New York Times'', June 22, 1980.\n* \"The Heavy Burden of the Past; Poets\", '