eb|author=Bloom, Harold|work=The New York Times| url=http://www.nybooks.com/authors/1343 |title=List of Bloom's contributions to ''The New York Review of Books''}}\n* {{cite book |title=Contemporary Literary Criticism |series=Contemporary Literary Criticism Series |chapter=Harold Bloom 1930\u2013 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/contemporarylite24detr/page/70 70]\u201383 |volume=24 |publisher=Gale |location=Detroit |year=1983 |isbn=9780810301115 |url=https://archive.org/details/contemporarylite24detr |url-access=registration }}\n* Burrow, Colin, \"The Magic Bloomschtick\" (review of Harold Bloom, ''The American Canon: Literary Genius from Emerson to Pynchon'', edited by [[David Mikics]], Library of America, October 2019, 426 pp., {{ISBN|978 1 59853 640 9}}), ''[[London Review of Books]]'', vol. 41, no. 22 (21 November 2019), pp. 21\u201325. \"Harold Bloom will be remembered as a great provoker \u2013 of thought, of laughter, and of resistance. He didn't permanently reconfigure the literary landscape, but the idiosyncratic path he tracked across it is one few could follow.\" (Final two sentences of Burrow's review, p. 25.)  \n* {{cite book|author=De Bolla, Peter| title=Harold Bloom: Toward Historical Rhetorics|publisher=Routledge|location=New York, NY|date= 1988}}\n* {{cite journal|journal=Dictionary of Literary Biography|volume= 67|title= Modern American Critics since 1955|publisher= Gale|date= 1988}}\n* {{cite book|author=Fite, David|title=Harold Bloom: The Rhetoric of Romantic Vision|url=https://archive.org/details/haroldbloomrheto0000fite|url-access=registration|publisher= University of Massachusetts Press |location=Amherst|date= 1985}}\n*{{cite book|author= Moynihan, Robert|title=A Recent Imagining: Interviews with Harold Bloom, Geoffrey Hartman, J. Hillis Miller, Paul De Man|publisher= Archon|date= 1986}}\n*{{cite book|author= Saurberg, Lars Ole|title=Versions of the Past\u2014Visions of the Future: The Canonical in the Criticism of T.S. Eliot, F.R. Leavis, 